WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.868 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.868 --> 00:00:14.820 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:14.820 --> 00:00:16.302 align:middle line:90%


00:00:16.302 --> 00:00:17.650 align:middle line:90%
>> It's the taboo.

00:00:17.650 --> 00:00:20.345 align:middle line:84%
It's the taboo,
basically of all time.

00:00:20.345 --> 00:00:21.220 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, of all time.

00:00:21.220 --> 00:00:23.137 align:middle line:84%
>> And right now, there
are a few more taboos.

00:00:23.137 --> 00:00:25.950 align:middle line:84%
We knocked off the
taboo against sex.

00:00:25.950 --> 00:00:27.050 align:middle line:90%
>> You did, personally.

00:00:27.050 --> 00:00:28.036 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

00:00:28.036 --> 00:00:28.836 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, well.

00:00:28.836 --> 00:00:31.000 align:middle line:90%
>> [LAUGHS]

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:32.380 align:middle line:90%
>> Drugs, of course.

00:00:32.380 --> 00:00:34.670 align:middle line:84%
Remember how upset
society got about drugs.

00:00:34.670 --> 00:00:35.470 align:middle line:90%
>> It still is.

00:00:35.470 --> 00:00:36.580 align:middle line:90%
>> The war on drugs?

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:39.450 align:middle line:84%
We certainly know
about that taboo.

00:00:39.450 --> 00:00:41.040 align:middle line:90%
The next thing was death.

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:44.850 align:middle line:84%
Everybody has deep
thoughts about death.

00:00:44.850 --> 00:00:48.000 align:middle line:90%
The ultimate taboo.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.360 align:middle line:84%
>> They blew up in this
world, this psychedelic world.

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:54.390 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it ended the 1950s.

00:00:54.390 --> 00:00:55.890 align:middle line:90%
>> It was all up for grabs.

00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:58.290 align:middle line:84%
It's hard to describe
what that felt like.

00:00:58.290 --> 00:01:00.720 align:middle line:84%
>> Leary and Alpert will be
remembered as cultural icons

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:04.470 align:middle line:84%
of the '60s especially, and very
influential people in not only

00:01:04.470 --> 00:01:06.860 align:middle line:84%
American culture,
but world culture.

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:09.750 align:middle line:84%
>> They are iconic figures
who stepped off the map.

00:01:09.750 --> 00:01:11.777 align:middle line:90%
They really paid heavily.

00:01:11.777 --> 00:01:14.360 align:middle line:84%
>> The use of psychedelic drugs,
such as marijuana, mescaline,

00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:18.600 align:middle line:84%
and LSD is out of control
in the United States today.

00:01:18.600 --> 00:01:21.100 align:middle line:90%
>> I knew he was an outlaw.

00:01:21.100 --> 00:01:24.130 align:middle line:10%
>> And you have to be quite
a bad-ass to get locked up

00:01:24.130 --> 00:01:25.450 align:middle line:10%
for your ideas.

00:01:25.450 --> 00:01:28.140 align:middle line:84%
>> We had a deep,
deep friendship.

00:01:28.140 --> 00:01:31.257 align:middle line:90%
But we also had a deep enmity.

00:01:31.257 --> 00:01:32.340 align:middle line:90%
>> We're all going to die.

00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:36.000 align:middle line:84%
Why not learn how to do it with
class and style and friendship

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.670 align:middle line:84%
as the climactic
expression of a life.

00:01:38.670 --> 00:01:44.820 align:middle line:10%
>> What Ram Dass did for our
culture was to open up a door

00:01:44.820 --> 00:01:50.050 align:middle line:10%
of spirituality by having
surrendered so completely

00:01:50.050 --> 00:01:50.850 align:middle line:10%
to love.

00:01:50.850 --> 00:02:08.030 align:middle line:90%


00:02:08.030 --> 00:02:13.360 align:middle line:84%
>> When you walked in, there
was a flash of total joy.

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:14.160 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:14.990 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, me too.

00:02:14.990 --> 00:02:15.540 align:middle line:90%
>> And love.

00:02:15.540 --> 00:02:17.123 align:middle line:10%
I don't know what
the words are, but--

00:02:17.123 --> 00:02:22.010 align:middle line:10%
>> See, in my mythology now,
I'd say you and I are connected

00:02:22.010 --> 00:02:26.690 align:middle line:10%
at a place where we both
danced through this incarnation

00:02:26.690 --> 00:02:31.340 align:middle line:10%
together, but that we have a
connection that is timeless

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:32.780 align:middle line:10%
in another sense of that.

00:02:32.780 --> 00:02:36.300 align:middle line:10%
And we're all beings that
know each other well,

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:37.697 align:middle line:10%
through many forms.

00:02:37.697 --> 00:02:41.040 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:44.654 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:02:44.654 --> 00:02:48.910 align:middle line:90%


00:02:48.910 --> 00:02:54.040 align:middle line:10%
>> I think one
incarnation is wonderful.

00:02:54.040 --> 00:02:59.680 align:middle line:10%
I mean, I started out a
Jewish boy from Boston,

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:02.830 align:middle line:10%
from psychology,
to psychedelics,

00:03:02.830 --> 00:03:07.100 align:middle line:10%
to Eastern mysticism.

00:03:07.100 --> 00:03:12.700 align:middle line:10%
And then to have
ended up Ram Dass,

00:03:12.700 --> 00:03:18.240 align:middle line:10%
just getting straight
on until it was gone.

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:19.040 align:middle line:90%
>> Who are you?

00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:19.940 align:middle line:90%
Who am I?

00:03:19.940 --> 00:03:22.490 align:middle line:90%
It's a very difficult question.

00:03:22.490 --> 00:03:24.200 align:middle line:84%
Throughout my life,
I was infatuated

00:03:24.200 --> 00:03:26.300 align:middle line:90%
by where the action was.

00:03:26.300 --> 00:03:29.090 align:middle line:84%
I never wanted to have
power, but I wanted to--

00:03:29.090 --> 00:03:33.230 align:middle line:84%
I ran for governor once
against Ronald Reagan.

00:03:33.230 --> 00:03:37.880 align:middle line:10%
I wanted to experience the
different theaters, or stages,

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:40.222 align:middle line:10%
or viewpoints of life.

00:03:40.222 --> 00:03:42.680 align:middle line:84%
I think I lived one of the most
interesting lives of anyone

00:03:42.680 --> 00:03:43.680 align:middle line:90%
in the 20th century.

00:03:43.680 --> 00:03:55.620 align:middle line:90%


00:03:55.620 --> 00:03:58.780 align:middle line:84%
>> In the summer of 1995,
Timothy Leary announced

00:03:58.780 --> 00:04:02.160 align:middle line:84%
to the world media that he'd
been diagnosed with inoperable

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:03.900 align:middle line:90%
prostate cancer.

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:05.190 align:middle line:90%
He was dying.

00:04:05.190 --> 00:04:10.040 align:middle line:10%
>> It's shocking that people
are not expected to talk about

00:04:10.040 --> 00:04:12.645 align:middle line:10%
their dying or to plan it.

00:04:12.645 --> 00:04:15.945 align:middle line:84%
It's certainly the
greatest adventure

00:04:15.945 --> 00:04:18.110 align:middle line:90%
and celebration of your life.

00:04:18.110 --> 00:04:20.640 align:middle line:84%
It should be the
process of moving on.

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:24.000 align:middle line:90%


00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:26.400 align:middle line:84%
>> He turned it into
a theater piece.

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:28.110 align:middle line:10%
He turned it into a poem.

00:04:28.110 --> 00:04:30.880 align:middle line:10%
He turned it into a dance.

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:33.840 align:middle line:10%
And it's just what he did
with all the rest of his life.

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:35.320 align:middle line:90%
It was a celebratory moment.

00:04:35.320 --> 00:04:38.792 align:middle line:90%


00:04:38.792 --> 00:04:40.250 align:middle line:90%
>> Living's a team sport.

00:04:40.250 --> 00:04:41.325 align:middle line:90%
Dying's a team sport.

00:04:41.325 --> 00:04:44.000 align:middle line:90%
Be open to new ideas.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.320 align:middle line:84%
Remember when people used to say
that LSD is an escapist drug?

00:04:47.320 --> 00:04:48.120 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:48.610 align:middle line:90%
I understand.

00:04:48.610 --> 00:04:49.345 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:04:49.345 --> 00:04:49.620 align:middle line:90%
It's not.

00:04:49.620 --> 00:04:50.450 align:middle line:90%
It's a confrontation.

00:04:50.450 --> 00:04:51.870 align:middle line:84%
>> One thing-- LSD is dangerous,
because you can't escape--

00:04:51.870 --> 00:04:53.500 align:middle line:90%
you've got 100 billion neurons.

00:04:53.500 --> 00:04:54.300 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:04:54.300 --> 00:04:56.910 align:middle line:84%
And my thing about death
is not escaping it.

00:04:56.910 --> 00:04:59.340 align:middle line:90%
I'm running toward Miss Death.

00:04:59.340 --> 00:05:02.190 align:middle line:84%
You can't turn this
over to the doctors.

00:05:02.190 --> 00:05:04.228 align:middle line:84%
You can't turn it
over to the priests.

00:05:04.228 --> 00:05:06.270 align:middle line:84%
You can't turn it over to
the medical profession.

00:05:06.270 --> 00:05:08.190 align:middle line:90%
Think for yourselves.

00:05:08.190 --> 00:05:10.230 align:middle line:84%
No government agency
or no profession

00:05:10.230 --> 00:05:12.060 align:middle line:84%
can solve these
problems for you.

00:05:12.060 --> 00:05:13.560 align:middle line:90%
I've got to do it for myself.

00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:15.180 align:middle line:84%
You've got to do
it for yourself.

00:05:15.180 --> 00:05:17.520 align:middle line:84%
And all the viewers have
got to do it for themselves.

00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:20.030 align:middle line:90%
Take charge of it.

00:05:20.030 --> 00:05:20.860 align:middle line:90%
Plan it.

00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:22.110 align:middle line:90%
Talk to your friends about it.

00:05:22.110 --> 00:05:25.575 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:05:25.575 --> 00:05:32.520 align:middle line:90%


00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:37.180 align:middle line:84%
>> Timothy Leary, born October
22, 1920, in Springfield,

00:05:37.180 --> 00:05:40.430 align:middle line:90%
Massachusetts, an only child.

00:05:40.430 --> 00:05:43.410 align:middle line:84%
>> And he took birth into
such an interesting tension,

00:05:43.410 --> 00:05:45.010 align:middle line:84%
in terms of, on
his mother's side,

00:05:45.010 --> 00:05:48.060 align:middle line:84%
very conservative
Irish-Catholic, very tight,

00:05:48.060 --> 00:05:50.520 align:middle line:90%
held in tight, very judgmental.

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:51.810 align:middle line:90%
His father was a dentist.

00:05:51.810 --> 00:05:53.415 align:middle line:84%
But from the Learys,
who were kind

00:05:53.415 --> 00:05:57.930 align:middle line:84%
of a wild, Irish,
drinking, divorcing,

00:05:57.930 --> 00:06:01.310 align:middle line:84%
"going off and running
away" type family.

00:06:01.310 --> 00:06:04.290 align:middle line:84%
>> I was a heavy
reader as a child.

00:06:04.290 --> 00:06:07.750 align:middle line:10%
And I spent hours and
hours as a kid studying

00:06:07.750 --> 00:06:10.710 align:middle line:10%
the heroic, and the
interesting, and the adventures

00:06:10.710 --> 00:06:13.090 align:middle line:10%
of people who were thinking.

00:06:13.090 --> 00:06:15.760 align:middle line:84%
>> Timothy had an
extraordinarily complex mind

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:17.890 align:middle line:90%
and subtle mind.

00:06:17.890 --> 00:06:21.915 align:middle line:84%
He liked the kind of multi-level
nature of consciousness a lot.

00:06:21.915 --> 00:06:23.290 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the fact
that James Joyce

00:06:23.290 --> 00:06:27.840 align:middle line:84%
was one of his favorite writers
is certainly a key, a blue.

00:06:27.840 --> 00:06:32.560 align:middle line:10%
And he was the
romantic Irish bard--

00:06:32.560 --> 00:06:36.400 align:middle line:10%
also the kind of
itinerant scholar,

00:06:36.400 --> 00:06:42.210 align:middle line:10%
the kind of rascally
person at the bar.

00:06:42.210 --> 00:06:46.750 align:middle line:84%
And he seemed to play
the role of a bad guy.

00:06:46.750 --> 00:06:49.360 align:middle line:84%
>> As Aldous Huxley
said, the good Dr.

00:06:49.360 --> 00:06:52.690 align:middle line:84%
Leary would serve our cause
and his own better if he could

00:06:52.690 --> 00:06:56.290 align:middle line:84%
resist his impulse to
cock snooks at authority.

00:06:56.290 --> 00:07:00.430 align:middle line:10%
There was a thing in Tim that
just liked to piss people off.

00:07:00.430 --> 00:07:07.900 align:middle line:10%
>> What he was at heart
was an Irish rebel.

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:11.380 align:middle line:10%
>> But like a good Irishman,
he could just pull tricks out

00:07:11.380 --> 00:07:12.940 align:middle line:10%
of the bag.

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:14.620 align:middle line:10%
And he did it continually.

00:07:14.620 --> 00:07:18.610 align:middle line:10%
>> He had a twinkle in his
eye and seemed leprechaun-ish

00:07:18.610 --> 00:07:20.740 align:middle line:10%
and mischievous.

00:07:20.740 --> 00:07:24.190 align:middle line:84%
>> Timothy's paternal
grandfather advised him to find

00:07:24.190 --> 00:07:27.700 align:middle line:90%
your own way, be one of a kind.

00:07:27.700 --> 00:07:30.970 align:middle line:84%
He acted on that guidance,
questioning authority

00:07:30.970 --> 00:07:33.790 align:middle line:90%
every chance he got.

00:07:33.790 --> 00:07:35.440 align:middle line:84%
Following in his
father's footsteps,

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:39.160 align:middle line:84%
Leary was a genial
hellraiser as a young man.

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:41.650 align:middle line:84%
At West Point, he was court
martialed for supplying liquor

00:07:41.650 --> 00:07:43.180 align:middle line:90%
to other cadets.

00:07:43.180 --> 00:07:45.550 align:middle line:84%
Eventually, he was
cleared of the charge

00:07:45.550 --> 00:07:47.690 align:middle line:90%
and left the academy.

00:07:47.690 --> 00:07:50.120 align:middle line:84%
Caught between the
Catholic desire to please

00:07:50.120 --> 00:07:52.730 align:middle line:84%
and a rebellious
nature that ran deep,

00:07:52.730 --> 00:07:54.650 align:middle line:84%
Tim spent his life
walking the edge

00:07:54.650 --> 00:07:59.650 align:middle line:90%
between conformity and chaos.

00:07:59.650 --> 00:08:01.520 align:middle line:84%
>> It's interesting
the things that happen.

00:08:01.520 --> 00:08:04.310 align:middle line:84%
He gets thrown out
of college for being

00:08:04.310 --> 00:08:05.990 align:middle line:90%
found in a girls' dormitory.

00:08:05.990 --> 00:08:10.130 align:middle line:10%
He gets given a jail sentence
for, originally, forty years,

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:13.450 align:middle line:10%
and it was then
reduced to 10, for--

00:08:13.450 --> 00:08:16.370 align:middle line:10%
what-- half an ounce of grass.

00:08:16.370 --> 00:08:19.580 align:middle line:84%
And there was a thing about
Timothy about right and wrong,

00:08:19.580 --> 00:08:21.680 align:middle line:84%
that he was busy
being a bad boy,

00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:24.530 align:middle line:84%
but, in the rascally
sense, the playful sense.

00:08:24.530 --> 00:08:26.500 align:middle line:90%
Timothy was not mean-spirited.

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:29.672 align:middle line:10%
He was absolutely
quite the opposite.

00:08:29.672 --> 00:08:32.630 align:middle line:90%


00:08:32.630 --> 00:08:38.960 align:middle line:84%
>> Richard Alpert, born April 6,
1931, in Boston, Massachusetts.

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:41.419 align:middle line:84%
His father, George
Alpert, was president

00:08:41.419 --> 00:08:44.460 align:middle line:84%
of the New York, New Haven,
and Hartford Railroad,

00:08:44.460 --> 00:08:47.120 align:middle line:84%
co-founder of
Brandeis University,

00:08:47.120 --> 00:08:50.690 align:middle line:84%
and a trustee of the
synagogue the family attended.

00:08:50.690 --> 00:08:54.410 align:middle line:84%
Studying psychology, Dick earned
his master's from Wesleyan

00:08:54.410 --> 00:08:56.690 align:middle line:90%
and a PhD at Stanford.

00:08:56.690 --> 00:09:00.320 align:middle line:10%
He taught on the faculties of
both Stanford and UC Berkeley.

00:09:00.320 --> 00:09:04.760 align:middle line:84%
Then, in 1958, he was appointed
assistant professor at Harvard.

00:09:04.760 --> 00:09:08.990 align:middle line:10%
A hometown success
at the age of 27.

00:09:08.990 --> 00:09:17.020 align:middle line:84%
>> I kept up a front
because I'd be scorned.

00:09:17.020 --> 00:09:22.400 align:middle line:84%
You just didn't talk
about homosexuality.

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:27.500 align:middle line:90%
My prep school-- oh, boy.

00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:33.360 align:middle line:90%
I went through hell, internally.

00:09:33.360 --> 00:09:37.900 align:middle line:84%
>> A part of it is the privilege
that he was brought into.

00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:40.160 align:middle line:90%
And part of it is the era.

00:09:40.160 --> 00:09:44.240 align:middle line:10%
It might be a key
variant in his life

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:49.100 align:middle line:10%
that made him really move into
the position of an outlier.

00:09:49.100 --> 00:09:56.660 align:middle line:84%
>> My homosexuality set
the stage for feeling like

00:09:56.660 --> 00:09:59.630 align:middle line:90%
an outcast.

00:09:59.630 --> 00:10:01.090 align:middle line:90%
Who am I to you--

00:10:01.090 --> 00:10:05.890 align:middle line:90%


00:10:05.890 --> 00:10:07.990 align:middle line:90%
in projection?

00:10:07.990 --> 00:10:09.398 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, you are--

00:10:09.398 --> 00:10:10.690 align:middle line:90%
we don't have the words for it.

00:10:10.690 --> 00:10:12.550 align:middle line:84%
But I'd say something
like soul mate,

00:10:12.550 --> 00:10:17.600 align:middle line:84%
or good friend and
long-term friend.

00:10:17.600 --> 00:10:19.420 align:middle line:90%
I don't want to expose this man.

00:10:19.420 --> 00:10:22.330 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's true that I'd
read more of the books.

00:10:22.330 --> 00:10:25.930 align:middle line:84%
But you were 10
times more streetwise

00:10:25.930 --> 00:10:27.130 align:middle line:90%
than I was when we met.

00:10:27.130 --> 00:10:28.280 align:middle line:90%
>> Really?

00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:28.540 align:middle line:90%
Really?

00:10:28.540 --> 00:10:29.340 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:31.590 align:middle line:84%
>> I always think of myself
as kind of a nebbish--

00:10:31.590 --> 00:10:35.340 align:middle line:84%
[LAUGHS] --lost
soul, very square.

00:10:35.340 --> 00:10:36.250 align:middle line:90%
And you picked me up.

00:10:36.250 --> 00:10:37.460 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh, yeah.

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:39.010 align:middle line:90%
>> I mean, you helped me.

00:10:39.010 --> 00:10:40.230 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

00:10:40.230 --> 00:10:42.605 align:middle line:84%
>> But you were also a very
scared Jewish boy that wanted

00:10:42.605 --> 00:10:43.405 align:middle line:90%
to--

00:10:43.405 --> 00:10:44.450 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes, I was also that.

00:10:44.450 --> 00:10:45.250 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:10:45.250 --> 00:10:52.810 align:middle line:90%


00:10:52.810 --> 00:10:55.520 align:middle line:84%
If you asked me for
the major discovery

00:10:55.520 --> 00:10:59.390 align:middle line:84%
about myself and my
life, it's the confidence

00:10:59.390 --> 00:11:05.450 align:middle line:84%
to think for myself
and to explore.

00:11:05.450 --> 00:11:07.610 align:middle line:84%
>> During the war,
Leary completed his

00:11:07.610 --> 00:11:10.670 align:middle line:84%
bachelor's in psychology and
was posted at the Army Medical

00:11:10.670 --> 00:11:13.090 align:middle line:90%
Corps hospital in Pennsylvania.

00:11:13.090 --> 00:11:16.100 align:middle line:84%
There, Tim met his
first wife, Marianne.

00:11:16.100 --> 00:11:18.650 align:middle line:10%
They were married in 1945.

00:11:18.650 --> 00:11:22.990 align:middle line:84%
He then got his masters in
psychology at Washington State.

00:11:22.990 --> 00:11:27.640 align:middle line:84%
In 1946, they moved to San
Francisco and started a family.

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:30.700 align:middle line:84%
Leary earned his PhD and
began clinical research

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:32.770 align:middle line:90%
at UC Berkeley.

00:11:32.770 --> 00:11:36.940 align:middle line:10%
There, he developed a definitive
test for personality assessment

00:11:36.940 --> 00:11:40.930 align:middle line:10%
and was published widely
in respected journals.

00:11:40.930 --> 00:11:43.060 align:middle line:84%
The American
Psychological Association

00:11:43.060 --> 00:11:45.790 align:middle line:84%
named his first book, "The
Interpersonal Diagnosis

00:11:45.790 --> 00:11:48.130 align:middle line:84%
of Personality," its
book of the year.

00:11:48.130 --> 00:11:50.680 align:middle line:90%


00:11:50.680 --> 00:11:53.230 align:middle line:84%
Both Leary and Marianne
were heavy drinkers.

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:57.430 align:middle line:84%
And Marianne suffered
from severe depression.

00:11:57.430 --> 00:12:00.580 align:middle line:84%
She committed suicide
in 1955, on the morning

00:12:00.580 --> 00:12:03.730 align:middle line:84%
of Tim's 35th birthday,
after hearing that he

00:12:03.730 --> 00:12:07.180 align:middle line:90%
had been having an affair.

00:12:07.180 --> 00:12:09.920 align:middle line:84%
Marianne's death haunted Tim
for the rest of his life.

00:12:09.920 --> 00:12:13.320 align:middle line:90%


00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:16.120 align:middle line:84%
In 1958, dissatisfied
with psychology,

00:12:16.120 --> 00:12:19.410 align:middle line:84%
which had a success rate, he
thought, no better than chance,

00:12:19.410 --> 00:12:21.990 align:middle line:84%
Leary moved with his two
children, Susan and Jack,

00:12:21.990 --> 00:12:24.450 align:middle line:90%
to Florence, Italy.

00:12:24.450 --> 00:12:26.880 align:middle line:84%
There, he met David
McLellan, the director

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:30.360 align:middle line:84%
of the Harvard Center
for Personality Research.

00:12:30.360 --> 00:12:32.160 align:middle line:84%
Leary explained that
he wanted to throw out

00:12:32.160 --> 00:12:35.490 align:middle line:84%
the old doctor-patient model
for psychological study

00:12:35.490 --> 00:12:37.710 align:middle line:84%
and get involved with
the subjects in real life

00:12:37.710 --> 00:12:39.870 align:middle line:90%
situations.

00:12:39.870 --> 00:12:41.550 align:middle line:10%
McLellan was impressed.

00:12:41.550 --> 00:12:46.620 align:middle line:10%
>> Leary was the
brightest psychologist.

00:12:46.620 --> 00:12:54.570 align:middle line:10%
But Harvard lured him
away by offering him

00:12:54.570 --> 00:13:00.530 align:middle line:10%
a three-year research project.

00:13:00.530 --> 00:13:04.010 align:middle line:84%
>> That summer, Timothy Leary
ate psychoactive mushrooms

00:13:04.010 --> 00:13:08.060 align:middle line:84%
for the first time in
Cuernavaca, Mexico.

00:13:08.060 --> 00:13:10.550 align:middle line:84%
They were offered to him
by a visiting East German

00:13:10.550 --> 00:13:14.360 align:middle line:84%
anthropologist who had heard
of their use among the Aztecs.

00:13:14.360 --> 00:13:18.340 align:middle line:84%
>> And he said,
here, take these.

00:13:18.340 --> 00:13:21.230 align:middle line:90%
They were interesting.

00:13:21.230 --> 00:13:23.790 align:middle line:84%
>> Over the next four hours,
he journeyed through his inner

00:13:23.790 --> 00:13:27.080 align:middle line:84%
landscapes and came
back a changed man.

00:13:27.080 --> 00:13:29.930 align:middle line:90%


00:13:29.930 --> 00:13:31.780 align:middle line:84%
Leary later told
Alpert that he had

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:35.170 align:middle line:84%
learned more about
the mind in four hours

00:13:35.170 --> 00:13:39.700 align:middle line:84%
than he had in his 15
years as a psychologist.

00:13:39.700 --> 00:13:43.710 align:middle line:84%
It was 1960, and he
was 40 years old.

00:13:43.710 --> 00:13:49.070 align:middle line:10%
>> Having an open
book on research--

00:13:49.070 --> 00:13:52.160 align:middle line:10%
anything he wanted to do.

00:13:52.160 --> 00:13:57.015 align:middle line:84%
He, of course, wanted to
research these substances.

00:13:57.015 --> 00:13:59.810 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:13:59.810 --> 00:14:05.420 align:middle line:84%
>> When I went to Harvard, there
was another young professor who

00:14:05.420 --> 00:14:07.640 align:middle line:84%
was a very lovable,
charismatic person.

00:14:07.640 --> 00:14:10.220 align:middle line:90%
And we joined up as a time.

00:14:10.220 --> 00:14:12.020 align:middle line:84%
Richard Alpert,
who's now Ram Dass,

00:14:12.020 --> 00:14:14.840 align:middle line:90%
has been more conservative.

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:17.960 align:middle line:84%
>> When I was at Harvard with
Timothy, I was so gung ho.

00:14:17.960 --> 00:14:21.380 align:middle line:84%
I had appointments in four
departments simultaneously,

00:14:21.380 --> 00:14:25.220 align:middle line:84%
and also research
contracts at Stanford.

00:14:25.220 --> 00:14:26.570 align:middle line:90%
>> Fantastically successful.

00:14:26.570 --> 00:14:29.660 align:middle line:10%
I mean, he had appointments
at Stanford and Harvard.

00:14:29.660 --> 00:14:31.610 align:middle line:10%
And he had a plane.

00:14:31.610 --> 00:14:32.800 align:middle line:10%
And he had a car.

00:14:32.800 --> 00:14:36.110 align:middle line:90%
And he was like a shining star.

00:14:36.110 --> 00:14:39.050 align:middle line:90%
He had tremendous charisma.

00:14:39.050 --> 00:14:43.730 align:middle line:10%
>> I was going to graduate at
Harvard between 1960 and 1964.

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:48.620 align:middle line:84%
I had met Dick
Alpert at a party.

00:14:48.620 --> 00:14:51.550 align:middle line:84%
I found him uncomfortable
to be around.

00:14:51.550 --> 00:14:55.520 align:middle line:84%
He seemed to be not
comfortable in his own being.

00:14:55.520 --> 00:14:59.180 align:middle line:84%
>> I was like Mr. Power
Player in academia.

00:14:59.180 --> 00:15:01.200 align:middle line:90%
Timothy was way outside of that.

00:15:01.200 --> 00:15:04.610 align:middle line:84%
Of all the colleagues
around me, he frightened me

00:15:04.610 --> 00:15:07.070 align:middle line:90%
because he was so free.

00:15:07.070 --> 00:15:10.880 align:middle line:84%
He was the only consciousness
on the faculty that

00:15:10.880 --> 00:15:14.150 align:middle line:84%
hadn't been co-opted by
Harvard, that wasn't impressed

00:15:14.150 --> 00:15:16.250 align:middle line:90%
with being at Harvard.

00:15:16.250 --> 00:15:19.350 align:middle line:84%
I saw you were
laughing at the system.

00:15:19.350 --> 00:15:21.530 align:middle line:84%
And I had no sense
of humor whatsoever.

00:15:21.530 --> 00:15:23.610 align:middle line:84%
>> You're not supposed
to laugh at Harvard.

00:15:23.610 --> 00:15:24.410 align:middle line:90%
>> I know.

00:15:24.410 --> 00:15:28.085 align:middle line:84%
There was nobody else in
Harvard laughing at it but you.

00:15:28.085 --> 00:15:30.890 align:middle line:84%
I began to sense what
a visionary he was,

00:15:30.890 --> 00:15:34.850 align:middle line:84%
that Timothy had the ability
to see outside of systems.

00:15:34.850 --> 00:15:38.910 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, he could
open things to where you go,

00:15:38.910 --> 00:15:41.750 align:middle line:84%
but it would take you a
while to get there maybe.

00:15:41.750 --> 00:15:43.340 align:middle line:90%
And he was doing that for me.

00:15:43.340 --> 00:15:44.190 align:middle line:90%
>> I didn't do that.

00:15:44.190 --> 00:15:44.990 align:middle line:90%
You did.

00:15:44.990 --> 00:15:45.790 align:middle line:90%
>> But the drug--

00:15:45.790 --> 00:15:47.900 align:middle line:84%
>> You freed me, but
you gave me the drug.

00:15:47.900 --> 00:15:51.490 align:middle line:90%
You enticed-- not enticed me.

00:15:51.490 --> 00:15:55.370 align:middle line:84%
You told me what the possibility
was, and I trusted you.

00:15:55.370 --> 00:15:58.490 align:middle line:90%


00:15:58.490 --> 00:16:02.170 align:middle line:10%
>> In the fall of 1960, Leary
discovered that Sandoz Limited,

00:16:02.170 --> 00:16:06.260 align:middle line:10%
a pharmaceutical company, would
send synthesized psilocybin

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:09.230 align:middle line:10%
to qualified researchers.

00:16:09.230 --> 00:16:12.530 align:middle line:84%
He had access to the active
ingredient of magic mushrooms.

00:16:12.530 --> 00:16:15.860 align:middle line:90%


00:16:15.860 --> 00:16:17.780 align:middle line:84%
Leary then set up
a research program

00:16:17.780 --> 00:16:22.130 align:middle line:84%
to investigate the
effects of psilocybin.

00:16:22.130 --> 00:16:25.070 align:middle line:84%
Staff members trained as
guides and took the drug

00:16:25.070 --> 00:16:28.160 align:middle line:84%
alongside volunteer subjects
in specially prepared

00:16:28.160 --> 00:16:30.980 align:middle line:90%
supportive settings.

00:16:30.980 --> 00:16:33.740 align:middle line:10%
This approach became
known as set and setting.

00:16:33.740 --> 00:16:36.510 align:middle line:10%


00:16:36.510 --> 00:16:38.880 align:middle line:10%
Careful evaluations were
made of each session.

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:43.020 align:middle line:90%


00:16:43.020 --> 00:16:46.740 align:middle line:84%
Alpert was away at UC Berkeley,
but that Leary took psilocybin

00:16:46.740 --> 00:16:49.940 align:middle line:84%
for the first time at Leary's
house in Newton Center.

00:16:49.940 --> 00:16:52.620 align:middle line:90%


00:16:52.620 --> 00:16:55.290 align:middle line:84%
It stripped him of the various
identities he had built up

00:16:55.290 --> 00:16:58.670 align:middle line:90%
in himself over 30 years.

00:16:58.670 --> 00:17:01.380 align:middle line:84%
He wrote, "I realize
that, although everything

00:17:01.380 --> 00:17:03.180 align:middle line:90%
by which I knew myself--

00:17:03.180 --> 00:17:05.579 align:middle line:84%
even my body and
this life itself--

00:17:05.579 --> 00:17:09.780 align:middle line:84%
was gone, still, I
was fully aware."

00:17:09.780 --> 00:17:15.839 align:middle line:84%
>> As professor went, and middle
class boy went, and pilot went,

00:17:15.839 --> 00:17:20.099 align:middle line:84%
and all of my games were
going off into the distance,

00:17:20.099 --> 00:17:21.599 align:middle line:90%
I got this terrible panic.

00:17:21.599 --> 00:17:25.589 align:middle line:84%
Because, indeed, I was
going to cease to exist.

00:17:25.589 --> 00:17:28.390 align:middle line:84%
And I got the panic, which
is the panic that precedes

00:17:28.390 --> 00:17:29.760 align:middle line:90%
the psychological death.

00:17:29.760 --> 00:17:33.320 align:middle line:84%
Because indeed, Richard Alpert
was dying at that point.

00:17:33.320 --> 00:17:35.370 align:middle line:84%
And the panic was,
no, stop, stop.

00:17:35.370 --> 00:17:39.390 align:middle line:84%
I've got to hold onto something
so I'll know who I am.

00:17:39.390 --> 00:17:41.460 align:middle line:84%
And Timothy-- the
wise, old Timothy--

00:17:41.460 --> 00:17:44.790 align:middle line:84%
always says things like,
trust your nervous system.

00:17:44.790 --> 00:17:47.550 align:middle line:90%
And you at dawn went home.

00:17:47.550 --> 00:17:48.350 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:17:48.350 --> 00:17:49.510 align:middle line:90%
>> And you were shoveling--

00:17:49.510 --> 00:17:50.310 align:middle line:90%
>> Snow.

00:17:50.310 --> 00:17:52.410 align:middle line:84%
>> --the snow in front of your
mother and father's house.

00:17:52.410 --> 00:17:54.535 align:middle line:84%
And your mother said, what
are you doing out there?

00:17:54.535 --> 00:17:55.530 align:middle line:90%
>> You idiot, come in.

00:17:55.530 --> 00:17:56.572 align:middle line:90%
It's 4:00 in the morning.

00:17:56.572 --> 00:17:58.000 align:middle line:90%
Nobody shovels snow.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:17:59.190 align:middle line:84%
>> You said, I love you,
Mom, or something like that.

00:17:59.190 --> 00:18:00.270 align:middle line:90%
>> And I said, I love you.

00:18:00.270 --> 00:18:01.687 align:middle line:84%
And I went back
to shoveling snow.

00:18:01.687 --> 00:18:04.350 align:middle line:84%
You freed me, at that
moment, from my mother.

00:18:04.350 --> 00:18:07.080 align:middle line:90%
That's what you did.

00:18:07.080 --> 00:18:10.410 align:middle line:84%
>> The psilocybin project was
widely supported and above

00:18:10.410 --> 00:18:11.550 align:middle line:90%
reproach.

00:18:11.550 --> 00:18:14.290 align:middle line:10%
The drug was legally
obtained from Sandoz,

00:18:14.290 --> 00:18:16.040 align:middle line:10%
the project
authorized by Harvard.

00:18:16.040 --> 00:18:20.580 align:middle line:90%


00:18:20.580 --> 00:18:22.990 align:middle line:10%
>> I heard about these
two professors at Harvard.

00:18:22.990 --> 00:18:25.360 align:middle line:10%
They were offering
to give people

00:18:25.360 --> 00:18:28.540 align:middle line:10%
psilocybin in return
for having them

00:18:28.540 --> 00:18:31.090 align:middle line:10%
write about their experiences.

00:18:31.090 --> 00:18:35.200 align:middle line:84%
I arranged to have a
session with Richard.

00:18:35.200 --> 00:18:37.120 align:middle line:84%
I felt very
comfortable with him.

00:18:37.120 --> 00:18:40.810 align:middle line:84%
So I thought, this can only
be a positive experience.

00:18:40.810 --> 00:18:46.640 align:middle line:84%
And it really confirmed a lot
of things that I had hoped

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:50.030 align:middle line:84%
were true, that I
had sort of glimpsed

00:18:50.030 --> 00:18:52.130 align:middle line:84%
at various times in my
life-- in other words,

00:18:52.130 --> 00:18:56.270 align:middle line:84%
that there was kind of a
larger reality than what

00:18:56.270 --> 00:19:00.750 align:middle line:84%
my everyday, humdrum
experiences were.

00:19:00.750 --> 00:19:04.950 align:middle line:84%
>> I read about mescaline, I
think after I graduated from

00:19:04.950 --> 00:19:07.770 align:middle line:84%
high school, and was
fascinated by it,

00:19:07.770 --> 00:19:10.920 align:middle line:84%
read everything I could
on it, wanted to try it.

00:19:10.920 --> 00:19:13.410 align:middle line:84%
When I got to
Harvard, Aldous Huxley

00:19:13.410 --> 00:19:15.690 align:middle line:84%
had come to MIT to give
a series of lectures

00:19:15.690 --> 00:19:17.710 align:middle line:90%
on visionary experience.

00:19:17.710 --> 00:19:21.813 align:middle line:84%
I found out that Leary and
Alpert were teaching at Harvard

00:19:21.813 --> 00:19:22.980 align:middle line:90%
and were interested in this.

00:19:22.980 --> 00:19:24.680 align:middle line:90%
So I went over.

00:19:24.680 --> 00:19:27.090 align:middle line:84%
I made an appointment,
and I met Leary.

00:19:27.090 --> 00:19:28.560 align:middle line:84%
I had a good
conversation with him.

00:19:28.560 --> 00:19:32.910 align:middle line:84%
He told me that he thought these
drugs were the most interesting

00:19:32.910 --> 00:19:34.240 align:middle line:90%
things he'd ever found.

00:19:34.240 --> 00:19:35.970 align:middle line:90%
And the potential was enormous.

00:19:35.970 --> 00:19:38.753 align:middle line:84%
He didn't see any
downside to them.

00:19:38.753 --> 00:19:40.920 align:middle line:84%
I asked him if I could be
a subject in his research.

00:19:40.920 --> 00:19:42.753 align:middle line:84%
And he told me that
they'd made an agreement

00:19:42.753 --> 00:19:45.270 align:middle line:84%
with the university that they
couldn't use undergraduates.

00:19:45.270 --> 00:19:48.780 align:middle line:84%
So I got a supply of mescaline,
independent of anything

00:19:48.780 --> 00:19:50.490 align:middle line:90%
to do with them.

00:19:50.490 --> 00:19:53.040 align:middle line:84%
I took it a number of times
with a group of friends of mine

00:19:53.040 --> 00:19:54.990 align:middle line:90%
who were undergraduates.

00:19:54.990 --> 00:19:57.270 align:middle line:84%
I had variable
experiences with it--

00:19:57.270 --> 00:19:59.550 align:middle line:90%
one quite powerful.

00:19:59.550 --> 00:20:02.460 align:middle line:84%
But I didn't know
what to do with that.

00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:05.340 align:middle line:84%
It seems to me, if I followed
the implications of that,

00:20:05.340 --> 00:20:06.510 align:middle line:90%
I would drop out of college.

00:20:06.510 --> 00:20:07.718 align:middle line:90%
And I didn't want to do that.

00:20:07.718 --> 00:20:13.050 align:middle line:10%
So I think I boxed all
that up and set it aside.

00:20:13.050 --> 00:20:15.810 align:middle line:84%
>> Branching out, the
professors organized a prisoner

00:20:15.810 --> 00:20:18.710 align:middle line:90%
rehabilitation project.

00:20:18.710 --> 00:20:21.860 align:middle line:10%
Psilocybin was given to selected
inmates at Concord State

00:20:21.860 --> 00:20:22.910 align:middle line:10%
Prison.

00:20:22.910 --> 00:20:25.730 align:middle line:10%
Their hope was to help them
break through the habits that

00:20:25.730 --> 00:20:30.030 align:middle line:10%
kept getting them rearrested.

00:20:30.030 --> 00:20:32.520 align:middle line:84%
Another famous study
had 30 seminary students

00:20:32.520 --> 00:20:36.240 align:middle line:84%
taking psilocybin at Boston
University Chapel during one

00:20:36.240 --> 00:20:39.410 align:middle line:90%
of the year's main services.

00:20:39.410 --> 00:20:42.990 align:middle line:84%
It became known as the
Good Friday Experiment.

00:20:42.990 --> 00:20:52.010 align:middle line:84%
>> There were 16 of us in this
small chapel who had ingested.

00:20:52.010 --> 00:21:00.220 align:middle line:10%
I very soon felt the
awe coming over me.

00:21:00.220 --> 00:21:03.410 align:middle line:84%
>> This was probably the
greatest Good Friday of 2,000

00:21:03.410 --> 00:21:04.247 align:middle line:90%
years.

00:21:04.247 --> 00:21:07.586 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:21:07.586 --> 00:21:10.450 align:middle line:90%


00:21:10.450 --> 00:21:14.380 align:middle line:10%
>> In the spring of 1962, just
as the psilocybin project was

00:21:14.380 --> 00:21:18.270 align:middle line:10%
becoming almost manageable, a
British researcher arrived from

00:21:18.270 --> 00:21:23.730 align:middle line:10%
England with a more powerful
psychoactive drug, LSD.

00:21:23.730 --> 00:21:26.880 align:middle line:84%
Lysergic acid
diethylamide was first

00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:30.330 align:middle line:84%
synthesized by Albert
Hofmann from a derivative

00:21:30.330 --> 00:21:36.870 align:middle line:84%
of ryegrass fungus at the Swiss
headquarters of Sandoz in 1938.

00:21:36.870 --> 00:21:38.520 align:middle line:10%
Five years later,
he accidentally

00:21:38.520 --> 00:21:41.430 align:middle line:10%
got some on his
skin and discovered

00:21:41.430 --> 00:21:46.582 align:middle line:10%
its mind-bending properties
during an epic bike ride home.

00:21:46.582 --> 00:21:50.534 align:middle line:90%
[THUNDER]

00:21:50.534 --> 00:22:17.750 align:middle line:90%


00:22:17.750 --> 00:22:19.940 align:middle line:84%
>> Hofmann not only
survived the ride,

00:22:19.940 --> 00:22:23.390 align:middle line:84%
but continued as a chemist
at Sandoz for many years.

00:22:23.390 --> 00:22:26.680 align:middle line:90%
He lived to be 102.

00:22:26.680 --> 00:22:29.110 align:middle line:84%
At first, Leary
resisted the idea

00:22:29.110 --> 00:22:31.900 align:middle line:84%
of including LSD in
the Harvard project.

00:22:31.900 --> 00:22:34.690 align:middle line:84%
Researching psilocybin
was pushing administrators

00:22:34.690 --> 00:22:36.860 align:middle line:90%
far enough.

00:22:36.860 --> 00:22:39.290 align:middle line:10%
Another issue was
the reputation LSD

00:22:39.290 --> 00:22:46.550 align:middle line:10%
had of being a mind control
drug researched by the military.

00:22:46.550 --> 00:22:48.470 align:middle line:84%
But his own experience
convinced Leary

00:22:48.470 --> 00:22:52.130 align:middle line:84%
that LSD held potential
for scientific discovery

00:22:52.130 --> 00:22:54.800 align:middle line:90%
far beyond that of psilocybin.

00:22:54.800 --> 00:22:56.510 align:middle line:90%
>> The LSD was interesting.

00:22:56.510 --> 00:22:59.720 align:middle line:84%
Because when he took
the LSD, he didn't

00:22:59.720 --> 00:23:02.430 align:middle line:90%
talk for about five days.

00:23:02.430 --> 00:23:06.320 align:middle line:84%
And I got afraid
we lost Timothy.

00:23:06.320 --> 00:23:09.740 align:middle line:84%
>> It's hard to describe what
it was like taking LSD under

00:23:09.740 --> 00:23:12.970 align:middle line:84%
the set and setting
of the early '60s.

00:23:12.970 --> 00:23:20.300 align:middle line:10%
The rending away from all of
these very intense paradigms

00:23:20.300 --> 00:23:24.800 align:middle line:10%
of authority and
monotheism and culture.

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:26.570 align:middle line:84%
>> As a good
lieutenant on the ship,

00:23:26.570 --> 00:23:29.150 align:middle line:84%
I sort of battened down the
hatches and told everybody not

00:23:29.150 --> 00:23:35.120 align:middle line:84%
to touch the stuff
and just to wait.

00:23:35.120 --> 00:23:38.000 align:middle line:84%
And then Timothy, finally,
when he was able to speak,

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:42.700 align:middle line:84%
it was more like, wow,
or, whew, or, yes.

00:23:42.700 --> 00:23:43.700 align:middle line:90%
And then we all started.

00:23:43.700 --> 00:23:46.720 align:middle line:90%


00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:49.410 align:middle line:84%
>> Leary and Alpert saw
their research as connected

00:23:49.410 --> 00:23:52.680 align:middle line:84%
to the centuries-long use
of psychotropic plants

00:23:52.680 --> 00:23:54.670 align:middle line:84%
by indigenous people
throughout the world.

00:23:54.670 --> 00:23:59.670 align:middle line:90%


00:23:59.670 --> 00:24:04.470 align:middle line:84%
Psychedelic, from the Greek
word "psyche" and "delos,"

00:24:04.470 --> 00:24:06.750 align:middle line:84%
literally means
mind manifesting.

00:24:06.750 --> 00:24:09.750 align:middle line:90%


00:24:09.750 --> 00:24:11.760 align:middle line:84%
After their sessions,
subjects reported

00:24:11.760 --> 00:24:15.220 align:middle line:90%
many common perceptions--

00:24:15.220 --> 00:24:18.180 align:middle line:90%
barriers dissolved.

00:24:18.180 --> 00:24:23.100 align:middle line:84%
Everything seemed alive,
even inanimate objects.

00:24:23.100 --> 00:24:26.800 align:middle line:84%
They felt a oneness
with everything.

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:33.220 align:middle line:84%
Colors and solid patterns
were transfixing, mesmerizing.

00:24:33.220 --> 00:24:37.630 align:middle line:84%
The experience seemed
to come in waves.

00:24:37.630 --> 00:24:41.440 align:middle line:84%
>> Psychotropic drugs, who
should not be recognized

00:24:41.440 --> 00:24:47.950 align:middle line:84%
as existing or valid tools,
were demonized and glorified

00:24:47.950 --> 00:24:49.470 align:middle line:84%
for the wrong
reasons in the '60s.

00:24:49.470 --> 00:24:50.660 align:middle line:90%
That's natural.

00:24:50.660 --> 00:24:52.380 align:middle line:84%
The thing is, know
what you're doing.

00:24:52.380 --> 00:24:59.010 align:middle line:90%


00:24:59.010 --> 00:25:01.730 align:middle line:84%
>> It is normal and natural
to seek altered states

00:25:01.730 --> 00:25:03.320 align:middle line:90%
of consciousness, high states.

00:25:03.320 --> 00:25:05.210 align:middle line:84%
We do it all the
time in various ways.

00:25:05.210 --> 00:25:08.750 align:middle line:84%
Drugs are one way of
getting into them.

00:25:08.750 --> 00:25:10.790 align:middle line:84%
Well, there was two
classes of psychedelics.

00:25:10.790 --> 00:25:12.860 align:middle line:84%
One is the ones
that are mescaline

00:25:12.860 --> 00:25:16.298 align:middle line:84%
and its relatives-- more
stimulants than the other ones.

00:25:16.298 --> 00:25:17.840 align:middle line:10%
The other ones,
called indoles, which

00:25:17.840 --> 00:25:22.130 align:middle line:10%
is LSD, and psilocybin,
and DMT, really

00:25:22.130 --> 00:25:27.090 align:middle line:10%
are remarkably light in their
effects on the physical body.

00:25:27.090 --> 00:25:31.070 align:middle line:84%
I think, as a group, these
drugs are very non-toxic.

00:25:31.070 --> 00:25:33.980 align:middle line:84%
The main dangers are
psychological ones, of people

00:25:33.980 --> 00:25:37.310 align:middle line:90%
becoming panicked, terrified.

00:25:37.310 --> 00:25:41.420 align:middle line:84%
But I think the positive
potentials are terrific.

00:25:41.420 --> 00:25:45.350 align:middle line:84%
>> LSD is not a drug like
alcohol or a barbiturate.

00:25:45.350 --> 00:25:51.650 align:middle line:84%
LSD is a chemical that contains
several hundred Encyclopedia

00:25:51.650 --> 00:25:52.490 align:middle line:90%
Britannicas.

00:25:52.490 --> 00:25:54.980 align:middle line:84%
So when you talk to
someone who's taken LSD,

00:25:54.980 --> 00:25:57.050 align:middle line:84%
or if you have a sitting
who's taking LSD,

00:25:57.050 --> 00:25:58.850 align:middle line:84%
his consciousness
being spun through

00:25:58.850 --> 00:26:02.120 align:middle line:84%
many, many different levels
of language, which are not

00:26:02.120 --> 00:26:05.210 align:middle line:84%
the language of English or
French or Latin, but chemical

00:26:05.210 --> 00:26:08.620 align:middle line:84%
languages of sound
and nervous system,

00:26:08.620 --> 00:26:14.120 align:middle line:84%
sense organs, which are
many millions of years old.

00:26:14.120 --> 00:26:17.150 align:middle line:84%
What's the reaction to taking
LSD if the person is unprepared

00:26:17.150 --> 00:26:21.830 align:middle line:84%
and he swallows this local
library of chemical messages?

00:26:21.830 --> 00:26:23.010 align:middle line:90%
He's confused.

00:26:23.010 --> 00:26:24.890 align:middle line:84%
He can be entranced
and delighted.

00:26:24.890 --> 00:26:26.380 align:middle line:90%
Or it can be very frightening.

00:26:26.380 --> 00:26:32.420 align:middle line:10%
>> The experiences, personally,
that I had with psychedelics

00:26:32.420 --> 00:26:35.630 align:middle line:10%
was all about opening my mind.

00:26:35.630 --> 00:26:40.040 align:middle line:84%
And it was always, for me,
about the spiritual journey.

00:26:40.040 --> 00:26:43.340 align:middle line:84%
It affected a whole
generation of people that way.

00:26:43.340 --> 00:26:47.620 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it ended the 1950s.

00:26:47.620 --> 00:26:51.110 align:middle line:84%
>> It was as though the
splitting of the atom was going

00:26:51.110 --> 00:26:54.260 align:middle line:84%
to be followed by another
kind of splitting.

00:26:54.260 --> 00:26:56.480 align:middle line:84%
But it was the breaking
open of the heart

00:26:56.480 --> 00:26:58.340 align:middle line:90%
and the opening of the mind.

00:26:58.340 --> 00:27:02.480 align:middle line:10%
>> The reason that I took LSD,
and I think many of us did,

00:27:02.480 --> 00:27:06.890 align:middle line:10%
is a hunger to be an explorer.

00:27:06.890 --> 00:27:12.650 align:middle line:84%
>> I think they made me aware
of the magic in the world,

00:27:12.650 --> 00:27:16.160 align:middle line:84%
of seeing things not just from
the scientific perspective.

00:27:16.160 --> 00:27:19.430 align:middle line:84%
They really connected
me with nature in a way

00:27:19.430 --> 00:27:21.230 align:middle line:90%
that I wasn't before.

00:27:21.230 --> 00:27:24.290 align:middle line:84%
They really showed
me the potential

00:27:24.290 --> 00:27:27.830 align:middle line:84%
of how changing things in
here changes things out there.

00:27:27.830 --> 00:27:29.620 align:middle line:84%
And that's been a
major theme of my work.

00:27:29.620 --> 00:27:32.990 align:middle line:90%


00:27:32.990 --> 00:27:36.830 align:middle line:84%
>> It's important to understand
that certain drugs really are

00:27:36.830 --> 00:27:38.420 align:middle line:90%
sacred substances.

00:27:38.420 --> 00:27:43.192 align:middle line:84%
If you are going to use
some of the sacred drugs,

00:27:43.192 --> 00:27:44.900 align:middle line:84%
you have to use them
in the right context

00:27:44.900 --> 00:27:46.280 align:middle line:90%
with the right people.

00:27:46.280 --> 00:27:50.630 align:middle line:84%
Timothy Leary and Richard
Alpert recognized this.

00:27:50.630 --> 00:27:53.510 align:middle line:84%
>> I think the early work that
they did with psychedelics was

00:27:53.510 --> 00:27:55.730 align:middle line:90%
very important.

00:27:55.730 --> 00:27:57.950 align:middle line:84%
They showed that set
and setting really

00:27:57.950 --> 00:28:00.590 align:middle line:84%
influenced the
experience greatly,

00:28:00.590 --> 00:28:02.720 align:middle line:84%
that the mindset of
the experimenters

00:28:02.720 --> 00:28:05.270 align:middle line:90%
greatly influenced the outcomes.

00:28:05.270 --> 00:28:08.120 align:middle line:84%
And they really demonstrated
positive potentials

00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:11.230 align:middle line:84%
of the use of psychedelics,
which, I think, just now,

00:28:11.230 --> 00:28:14.730 align:middle line:84%
is becoming a focus
of attention again.

00:28:14.730 --> 00:28:18.660 align:middle line:84%
>> Doctors Joan Halifax and
Stan Grof were among the first

00:28:18.660 --> 00:28:21.840 align:middle line:84%
to research the use of
psychedelics with the dying--

00:28:21.840 --> 00:28:26.630 align:middle line:84%
in their case, terminal
cancer patients in 1967.

00:28:26.630 --> 00:28:29.780 align:middle line:84%
>> In the dying process,
there's often a lot of fear.

00:28:29.780 --> 00:28:32.480 align:middle line:84%
And I think psychedelics make
it possible to step aside

00:28:32.480 --> 00:28:36.080 align:middle line:84%
from that and observe what's
happening dispassionately.

00:28:36.080 --> 00:28:40.070 align:middle line:84%
A guided psychedelic
experience in a dying person

00:28:40.070 --> 00:28:44.090 align:middle line:84%
often enables that
person to drastically cut

00:28:44.090 --> 00:28:46.970 align:middle line:84%
doses of opiates for
pain relief, which

00:28:46.970 --> 00:28:48.860 align:middle line:90%
kept consciousness clear.

00:28:48.860 --> 00:28:51.380 align:middle line:84%
It often greatly
facilitated communication

00:28:51.380 --> 00:28:54.890 align:middle line:84%
with family and friends,
where, before, there

00:28:54.890 --> 00:28:58.320 align:middle line:84%
was no honest communication
always going on.

00:28:58.320 --> 00:29:00.310 align:middle line:84%
And it made the
dying process easier.

00:29:00.310 --> 00:29:05.270 align:middle line:84%
And so it was strongly positive
results of these studies.

00:29:05.270 --> 00:29:07.780 align:middle line:84%
So I think surrounding the
use of drugs with ritual,

00:29:07.780 --> 00:29:10.150 align:middle line:84%
making the occasions
of taking them special,

00:29:10.150 --> 00:29:13.250 align:middle line:84%
paying great attention
set and setting,

00:29:13.250 --> 00:29:18.340 align:middle line:84%
is all part of minimizing
their potential for harm.

00:29:18.340 --> 00:29:20.660 align:middle line:84%
>> We used to use "The
Tibetan Book of the Dead"

00:29:20.660 --> 00:29:23.600 align:middle line:84%
as a manual for
psychedelic trips.

00:29:23.600 --> 00:29:27.170 align:middle line:84%
And that really is a
manual of leaving your body

00:29:27.170 --> 00:29:30.400 align:middle line:84%
and going into what
they call a Bardo state.

00:29:30.400 --> 00:29:33.680 align:middle line:84%
And it's a manual
for death, really.

00:29:33.680 --> 00:29:38.330 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, the drug literature,
going back to William James

00:29:38.330 --> 00:29:42.440 align:middle line:84%
and the Harvard people 100
years ago, they always said,

00:29:42.440 --> 00:29:44.600 align:middle line:84%
it's a dying experience,
it's a death experience,

00:29:44.600 --> 00:29:49.310 align:middle line:84%
that there's a classic mystic
thing of joy and wonder,

00:29:49.310 --> 00:29:54.350 align:middle line:84%
which I'm not advocating,
boys and girls.

00:29:54.350 --> 00:29:56.450 align:middle line:84%
Like anything else,
it's complicated.

00:29:56.450 --> 00:29:58.460 align:middle line:90%
I'm very cautious.

00:29:58.460 --> 00:30:00.230 align:middle line:84%
I've taken almost
every drug there is.

00:30:00.230 --> 00:30:02.930 align:middle line:84%
But the reason I can
survive as well as I do--

00:30:02.930 --> 00:30:07.430 align:middle line:84%
I'm prudent, and I'm
careful, and I try

00:30:07.430 --> 00:30:10.400 align:middle line:90%
to find out what's involved.

00:30:10.400 --> 00:30:13.230 align:middle line:84%
20 years ago, we knew almost
nothing about the brain.

00:30:13.230 --> 00:30:16.700 align:middle line:90%
Now we know 120 billion neurons.

00:30:16.700 --> 00:30:20.210 align:middle line:84%
Every neuron in your brain
has 10,000 connections.

00:30:20.210 --> 00:30:22.820 align:middle line:84%
It's going to take
us decades to begin

00:30:22.820 --> 00:30:25.820 align:middle line:84%
to understand the magnificence
and the complexity

00:30:25.820 --> 00:30:31.450 align:middle line:84%
of this brain which creates
the realities we inhabit.

00:30:31.450 --> 00:30:34.030 align:middle line:84%
>> According to Leary, we
use but a small percentage

00:30:34.030 --> 00:30:36.280 align:middle line:84%
of our nervous
system's capacity,

00:30:36.280 --> 00:30:39.100 align:middle line:84%
that we've learned over
thousands of years to restrict

00:30:39.100 --> 00:30:43.150 align:middle line:84%
the use of our brains so
we can function in society.

00:30:43.150 --> 00:30:47.770 align:middle line:84%
Psychedelics open the full
landscape of our minds.

00:30:47.770 --> 00:30:50.800 align:middle line:84%
>> It was as if all these did
was accentuate the direction

00:30:50.800 --> 00:30:56.410 align:middle line:84%
his life was always going in,
freeing himself from systems,

00:30:56.410 --> 00:31:00.020 align:middle line:84%
freeing himself from all of
the ways that our mind creates

00:31:00.020 --> 00:31:00.820 align:middle line:90%
our reality.

00:31:00.820 --> 00:31:05.190 align:middle line:90%


00:31:05.190 --> 00:31:08.255 align:middle line:84%
>> Mythic heroes travel unknown
oceans in search of adventure

00:31:08.255 --> 00:31:11.200 align:middle line:90%
and new lands.

00:31:11.200 --> 00:31:13.630 align:middle line:84%
American astronauts were
about to launch themselves

00:31:13.630 --> 00:31:16.500 align:middle line:90%
into outer space.

00:31:16.500 --> 00:31:19.440 align:middle line:84%
In the 1960s, Leary and
Alpert dedicated themselves

00:31:19.440 --> 00:31:22.125 align:middle line:84%
to exploring the
nature of innerspace.

00:31:22.125 --> 00:31:24.000 align:middle line:84%
>> That's the word
Timothy and I always used.

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:27.450 align:middle line:84%
That's the mythic level that
Timothy and I lived at, was,

00:31:27.450 --> 00:31:29.460 align:middle line:90%
we were adventurers.

00:31:29.460 --> 00:31:35.270 align:middle line:84%
>> They averaged one LSD session
per week and took heroic doses.

00:31:35.270 --> 00:31:37.820 align:middle line:84%
They saw themselves as
psychedelic adventurers,

00:31:37.820 --> 00:31:42.660 align:middle line:84%
exploring the nature of reality,
encountering both heaven

00:31:42.660 --> 00:31:43.460 align:middle line:90%
and hell.

00:31:43.460 --> 00:31:47.120 align:middle line:90%


00:31:47.120 --> 00:31:49.760 align:middle line:84%
They openly shared the
results of their work,

00:31:49.760 --> 00:31:51.890 align:middle line:90%
encouraging others to join them.

00:31:51.890 --> 00:31:55.130 align:middle line:84%
LSD was, at that time,
still fully legal.

00:31:55.130 --> 00:31:59.990 align:middle line:84%
It was an innocent
time and a wild ride.

00:31:59.990 --> 00:32:03.650 align:middle line:84%
>> Driving up to Sandoz
in New Jersey in the huge,

00:32:03.650 --> 00:32:08.480 align:middle line:84%
black railroad limousine that
I had from my father with

00:32:08.480 --> 00:32:10.490 align:middle line:84%
railroad wheels
on the end of it.

00:32:10.490 --> 00:32:14.120 align:middle line:84%
And Timothy and I are driving up
to buy this huge amount of LSD

00:32:14.120 --> 00:32:15.980 align:middle line:90%
as Harvard professors.

00:32:15.980 --> 00:32:18.410 align:middle line:84%
There was so many
of those, just one

00:32:18.410 --> 00:32:21.490 align:middle line:90%
after another after another.

00:32:21.490 --> 00:32:24.200 align:middle line:84%
>> Ever the scientists, Leary
and Alpert published articles

00:32:24.200 --> 00:32:27.050 align:middle line:84%
in journals and delivered
papers at conferences.

00:32:27.050 --> 00:32:28.160 align:middle line:90%
The word was out.

00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:31.010 align:middle line:10%
And their program was
becoming popular--

00:32:31.010 --> 00:32:32.500 align:middle line:10%
maybe too popular.

00:32:32.500 --> 00:32:35.000 align:middle line:10%
>> It ended up so many graduate
students wanted to work with

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.820 align:middle line:10%
Leary, and almost all the
other graduate professors lost

00:32:37.820 --> 00:32:40.460 align:middle line:10%
student assistants, you
see, which pissed them off,

00:32:40.460 --> 00:32:41.360 align:middle line:10%
of course.

00:32:41.360 --> 00:32:43.020 align:middle line:84%
>> Independently,
about that same time,

00:32:43.020 --> 00:32:46.160 align:middle line:84%
I had joined the editorial
board of "The Harvard Crimson,"

00:32:46.160 --> 00:32:48.020 align:middle line:90%
the newspaper.

00:32:48.020 --> 00:32:52.880 align:middle line:84%
And there were stories
beginning to go around

00:32:52.880 --> 00:32:57.590 align:middle line:84%
about the drug experiments at
Harvard and Leary and Alpert.

00:32:57.590 --> 00:33:00.080 align:middle line:84%
And I was the only person
that had knowledge of that.

00:33:00.080 --> 00:33:03.740 align:middle line:84%
And so it was logical that
I became the reporter who

00:33:03.740 --> 00:33:05.120 align:middle line:90%
dealt with that.

00:33:05.120 --> 00:33:11.690 align:middle line:84%
>> Psilocybin was to be given
only to graduate students.

00:33:11.690 --> 00:33:16.010 align:middle line:90%
But there was one slip.

00:33:16.010 --> 00:33:21.430 align:middle line:84%
>> That guy that I
turned on-- one person--

00:33:21.430 --> 00:33:25.780 align:middle line:84%
was somebody to whom
I was attracted.

00:33:25.780 --> 00:33:28.120 align:middle line:84%
>> I was in a very
difficult role in that.

00:33:28.120 --> 00:33:30.340 align:middle line:84%
For one thing, I had
taken these drugs.

00:33:30.340 --> 00:33:32.410 align:middle line:84%
I had positive
feelings for them.

00:33:32.410 --> 00:33:34.510 align:middle line:90%
But I had a kind of dual life.

00:33:34.510 --> 00:33:37.360 align:middle line:84%
I was this straight
undergraduate

00:33:37.360 --> 00:33:41.008 align:middle line:84%
who was doing this
investigative reporting.

00:33:41.008 --> 00:33:43.300 align:middle line:84%
>> I think he wrote an article
in "The Harvard Crimson"

00:33:43.300 --> 00:33:44.740 align:middle line:90%
talking about this.

00:33:44.740 --> 00:33:48.100 align:middle line:10%
And the parents of this
one boy found out about it,

00:33:48.100 --> 00:33:51.830 align:middle line:10%
and they went to the officials
at Harvard, and said,

00:33:51.830 --> 00:33:53.830 align:middle line:10%
what's going on here?

00:33:53.830 --> 00:34:01.540 align:middle line:10%
>> The dean of Harvard said,
if he didn't squeal on me,

00:34:01.540 --> 00:34:04.840 align:middle line:10%
they're not going to
give him the diploma.

00:34:04.840 --> 00:34:11.469 align:middle line:84%
>> I played a key role in
getting information which

00:34:11.469 --> 00:34:17.139 align:middle line:84%
eventually led to Alpert's
being fired in 1963.

00:34:17.139 --> 00:34:18.219 align:middle line:90%
Leary was never fired.

00:34:18.219 --> 00:34:20.530 align:middle line:90%
He quit voluntarily.

00:34:20.530 --> 00:34:23.949 align:middle line:84%
That story was front page
news on "The New York Times."

00:34:23.949 --> 00:34:26.590 align:middle line:84%
And I think that was
probably the first time

00:34:26.590 --> 00:34:29.320 align:middle line:84%
that most Americans had ever
heard of psychedelic drugs,

00:34:29.320 --> 00:34:31.210 align:middle line:90%
or LSD, or mushrooms.

00:34:31.210 --> 00:34:36.310 align:middle line:84%
So I do think that whole episode
is what exploded this out

00:34:36.310 --> 00:34:39.880 align:middle line:84%
of Harvard, into the
nation and the Culture

00:34:39.880 --> 00:34:43.159 align:middle line:84%
>> Of course, this was a bit
of a shock, to put it mildly,

00:34:43.159 --> 00:34:46.170 align:middle line:84%
to Richard, who had been the
one who was on the tenure track.

00:34:46.170 --> 00:34:50.219 align:middle line:10%
And he had his career all sort
of mapped out, he thought.

00:34:50.219 --> 00:34:51.760 align:middle line:10%
>> You were on the tenure track.

00:34:51.760 --> 00:34:52.640 align:middle line:10%
>> I know I was.

00:34:52.640 --> 00:34:53.440 align:middle line:90%
And you laugh.

00:34:53.440 --> 00:34:54.252 align:middle line:90%
And you laugh.

00:34:54.252 --> 00:34:55.960 align:middle line:84%
>> If it weren't for
me, you would be a--

00:34:55.960 --> 00:34:57.083 align:middle line:90%
>> I'd be somebody today.

00:34:57.083 --> 00:34:58.000 align:middle line:90%
>> --retired Harvard--

00:34:58.000 --> 00:34:59.300 align:middle line:90%
>> You blew me apart.

00:34:59.300 --> 00:35:00.100 align:middle line:90%
>> I know it.

00:35:00.100 --> 00:35:01.360 align:middle line:84%
>> I would have been
something today.

00:35:01.360 --> 00:35:01.810 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:35:01.810 --> 00:35:03.040 align:middle line:90%
I ruined your academic career.

00:35:03.040 --> 00:35:03.840 align:middle line:90%
>> You did.

00:35:03.840 --> 00:35:06.690 align:middle line:90%
You absolutely did.

00:35:06.690 --> 00:35:08.610 align:middle line:84%
What happened was,
you were the one

00:35:08.610 --> 00:35:12.800 align:middle line:84%
that showed me that it
was possible to escape

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:15.600 align:middle line:90%
from the system.

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:16.800 align:middle line:90%
You really did.

00:35:16.800 --> 00:35:19.020 align:middle line:10%
It's been hard for me
to really understand

00:35:19.020 --> 00:35:21.700 align:middle line:10%
how I was ready to hear that.

00:35:21.700 --> 00:35:22.500 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:35:22.500 --> 00:35:24.480 align:middle line:90%
>> You know?

00:35:24.480 --> 00:35:28.710 align:middle line:84%
>> Timothy's contract at Harvard
ended soon after Dick was fired

00:35:28.710 --> 00:35:30.550 align:middle line:90%
in the spring of '63.

00:35:30.550 --> 00:35:32.070 align:middle line:84%
They desperately
wanted to continue

00:35:32.070 --> 00:35:36.270 align:middle line:84%
their work, which was becoming
highly controversial, but still

00:35:36.270 --> 00:35:37.590 align:middle line:90%
legal.

00:35:37.590 --> 00:35:39.000 align:middle line:90%
Where could they go?

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:42.390 align:middle line:84%
>> Just by chance, my brothers
inherited quite a bit of money.

00:35:42.390 --> 00:35:45.450 align:middle line:10%
And they had decided, with this
money, as a good investment,

00:35:45.450 --> 00:35:50.650 align:middle line:10%
to buy this huge property
in Millbrook, New York.

00:35:50.650 --> 00:35:52.780 align:middle line:84%
On the property with
an old house there

00:35:52.780 --> 00:35:54.750 align:middle line:90%
that was the original house.

00:35:54.750 --> 00:35:57.430 align:middle line:84%
And it belonged to the person
who developed the property back

00:35:57.430 --> 00:36:01.926 align:middle line:84%
in the late 19th,
early 20th century.

00:36:01.926 --> 00:36:04.080 align:middle line:84%
I kind of wanted it to
be haunted, you know?

00:36:04.080 --> 00:36:06.860 align:middle line:84%
It was huge, and lots of
turrets and curved glass.

00:36:06.860 --> 00:36:08.850 align:middle line:90%
It was really beautiful.

00:36:08.850 --> 00:36:10.210 align:middle line:90%
And so I talked to my brothers.

00:36:10.210 --> 00:36:11.560 align:middle line:90%
They weren't going to use it.

00:36:11.560 --> 00:36:13.018 align:middle line:84%
And they said,
sure, we'll rent you

00:36:13.018 --> 00:36:14.940 align:middle line:90%
the house for a dollar a year.

00:36:14.940 --> 00:36:18.640 align:middle line:84%
>> With Tim's children Susan and
Jack and a potpourri of friends

00:36:18.640 --> 00:36:21.580 align:middle line:84%
and acquaintances, the two
men launched into a life

00:36:21.580 --> 00:36:22.500 align:middle line:90%
of communal living.

00:36:22.500 --> 00:36:26.540 align:middle line:90%


00:36:26.540 --> 00:36:28.925 align:middle line:84%
That fall, President John
F. Kennedy was assassinated.

00:36:28.925 --> 00:36:31.610 align:middle line:90%
[GUNSHOT]

00:36:31.610 --> 00:36:37.042 align:middle line:84%
The decade had taken
a very nasty turn.

00:36:37.042 --> 00:36:39.250 align:middle line:84%
At Millbrook, the scientists
continued their research

00:36:39.250 --> 00:36:42.430 align:middle line:84%
into 1964, adapting
the old house

00:36:42.430 --> 00:36:44.590 align:middle line:90%
to its hipper inhabitants.

00:36:44.590 --> 00:36:47.530 align:middle line:84%
It soon became a second home
to artists and academics,

00:36:47.530 --> 00:36:49.090 align:middle line:90%
musicians and scientists.

00:36:49.090 --> 00:36:52.060 align:middle line:90%


00:36:52.060 --> 00:36:56.090 align:middle line:84%
Meanwhile, on the west coast,
the '60s were heating up.

00:36:56.090 --> 00:36:57.790 align:middle line:84%
The free speech
movement in Berkeley

00:36:57.790 --> 00:37:00.280 align:middle line:84%
began a reinvigoration
of democracy

00:37:00.280 --> 00:37:05.260 align:middle line:84%
that would lead to the
Summer of Love in 1967.

00:37:05.260 --> 00:37:10.990 align:middle line:84%
LSD, acid, was
often shared freely.

00:37:10.990 --> 00:37:13.660 align:middle line:10%
Years later, it became
known that the CIA ran

00:37:13.660 --> 00:37:17.950 align:middle line:10%
secret experiments with
LSD in the 1950s and 1960s,

00:37:17.950 --> 00:37:20.920 align:middle line:10%
hoping to find a way to
use the drug in warfare.

00:37:20.920 --> 00:37:22.510 align:middle line:84%
Inevitably, some
of their subjects

00:37:22.510 --> 00:37:25.730 align:middle line:84%
began using the
chemicals on their own.

00:37:25.730 --> 00:37:30.130 align:middle line:84%
Ken Kesey had first taken LSD
as part of a CIA-funded research

00:37:30.130 --> 00:37:33.460 align:middle line:84%
project while working
in a mental hospital.

00:37:33.460 --> 00:37:35.350 align:middle line:10%
Later, he and the
Merry Pranksters

00:37:35.350 --> 00:37:40.030 align:middle line:10%
held acid tests, giving
LSD to hundreds, much

00:37:40.030 --> 00:37:43.240 align:middle line:10%
to the dismay of the
scientists at Millbrook.

00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:46.300 align:middle line:84%
>> I have never urged
indiscriminate use of LSD.

00:37:46.300 --> 00:37:49.120 align:middle line:84%
And I have never
propagandized for LSD.

00:37:49.120 --> 00:37:51.040 align:middle line:84%
Strangely enough,
my position on LSD

00:37:51.040 --> 00:37:55.030 align:middle line:84%
is exactly that of the President
Johnson administration.

00:37:55.030 --> 00:37:57.220 align:middle line:84%
I believe that the
present laws which

00:37:57.220 --> 00:38:01.523 align:middle line:84%
penalize sale and
manufacture of LSD are right.

00:38:01.523 --> 00:38:03.940 align:middle line:10%
>> Meanwhile, I'm hearing out
of west coast that they were

00:38:03.940 --> 00:38:07.830 align:middle line:10%
filling a bathtub full of LSD
and feeding it to anybody that

00:38:07.830 --> 00:38:13.510 align:middle line:10%
wanted to come in and drink as
much as they wanted and playing

00:38:13.510 --> 00:38:14.620 align:middle line:10%
crazy music for them.

00:38:14.620 --> 00:38:18.140 align:middle line:84%
And I thought, this
was fucking drug abuse.

00:38:18.140 --> 00:38:21.070 align:middle line:10%
>> The use of psychedelic drugs,
such as marijuana, mescaline,

00:38:21.070 --> 00:38:24.400 align:middle line:10%
LSD, is out of control in
the United States today.

00:38:24.400 --> 00:38:31.300 align:middle line:90%


00:38:31.300 --> 00:38:34.330 align:middle line:84%
>> Over four years of communal
living at Millbrook and scores

00:38:34.330 --> 00:38:37.160 align:middle line:84%
of shared psilocybin
and LSD sessions,

00:38:37.160 --> 00:38:39.850 align:middle line:84%
Leary and Alpert developed
a close and trusting

00:38:39.850 --> 00:38:41.350 align:middle line:90%
relationship.

00:38:41.350 --> 00:38:43.660 align:middle line:84%
Richard took on a
domestic, motherly role,

00:38:43.660 --> 00:38:47.390 align:middle line:84%
becoming closer to Timothy's
children than Tim was himself.

00:38:47.390 --> 00:38:51.130 align:middle line:84%
>> And I got into the really
conscious thing in my mind that

00:38:51.130 --> 00:38:55.000 align:middle line:84%
I could justify my life
being a support system

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:57.680 align:middle line:84%
for Timothy's vision
to find expression.

00:38:57.680 --> 00:38:59.410 align:middle line:90%
So it meant raising money.

00:38:59.410 --> 00:39:00.640 align:middle line:90%
It meant raising children.

00:39:00.640 --> 00:39:01.450 align:middle line:90%
It meant cooking.

00:39:01.450 --> 00:39:04.380 align:middle line:90%
It meant getting housing.

00:39:04.380 --> 00:39:08.830 align:middle line:84%
It meant moving Jeeps
and stuff to islands

00:39:08.830 --> 00:39:10.540 align:middle line:90%
we were being thrown off.

00:39:10.540 --> 00:39:12.200 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it was incredible.

00:39:12.200 --> 00:39:15.530 align:middle line:90%
It meant setting up foundations.

00:39:15.530 --> 00:39:17.950 align:middle line:84%
It was all the public
relations stuff

00:39:17.950 --> 00:39:20.710 align:middle line:84%
to try to keep the game
from getting out of hand.

00:39:20.710 --> 00:39:24.610 align:middle line:84%
>> Richard, do you know
how to operate this?

00:39:24.610 --> 00:39:28.625 align:middle line:84%
>> In December 1964,
Leary married again.

00:39:28.625 --> 00:39:30.480 align:middle line:84%
>> The two studs
come in the front.

00:39:30.480 --> 00:39:32.722 align:middle line:90%
So this goes in the back.

00:39:32.722 --> 00:39:33.688 align:middle line:90%
You need a stud.

00:39:33.688 --> 00:39:35.140 align:middle line:90%
>> Where is the stud?

00:39:35.140 --> 00:39:36.400 align:middle line:90%
Gunther, you got the studs?

00:39:36.400 --> 00:39:37.200 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:39:37.200 --> 00:39:38.330 align:middle line:90%
They're over there.

00:39:38.330 --> 00:39:40.720 align:middle line:84%
>> Peggy Hitchcock had
introduced him to the beautiful

00:39:40.720 --> 00:39:43.810 align:middle line:84%
fashion model Nena,
and they fell in love.

00:39:43.810 --> 00:39:49.057 align:middle line:90%


00:39:49.057 --> 00:39:50.970 align:middle line:84%
>> Remember as much of
the vows as you can.

00:39:50.970 --> 00:39:51.460 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes, sir.

00:39:51.460 --> 00:39:52.260 align:middle line:90%
>> And I will.

00:39:52.260 --> 00:39:53.860 align:middle line:90%
>> I will.

00:39:53.860 --> 00:39:56.800 align:middle line:84%
>> They were married at a
chapel in the nearby town.

00:39:56.800 --> 00:39:57.940 align:middle line:90%
Dick was best man.

00:39:57.940 --> 00:40:02.270 align:middle line:90%
[CHURCH BELLS RINGING]

00:40:02.270 --> 00:40:04.450 align:middle line:84%
Timothy and Nena set
off on a world tour,

00:40:04.450 --> 00:40:06.610 align:middle line:84%
visiting Japan and
India in a quest

00:40:06.610 --> 00:40:08.890 align:middle line:90%
for spiritual understanding.

00:40:08.890 --> 00:40:11.930 align:middle line:84%
But by the time they
returned to Millbrook,

00:40:11.930 --> 00:40:14.840 align:middle line:90%
their marriage was over.

00:40:14.840 --> 00:40:18.100 align:middle line:84%
Leary would eventually
marry five times.

00:40:18.100 --> 00:40:22.490 align:middle line:84%
His best efforts never went
into sustaining relationships.

00:40:22.490 --> 00:40:26.310 align:middle line:84%
>> In his life, there was a big
disconnect between his heart

00:40:26.310 --> 00:40:27.110 align:middle line:90%
and his mind.

00:40:27.110 --> 00:40:31.200 align:middle line:10%
And his mind was
completely in charge always

00:40:31.200 --> 00:40:34.040 align:middle line:10%
and the heart kind
of got left behind.

00:40:34.040 --> 00:40:35.550 align:middle line:10%
>> Intimacy.

00:40:35.550 --> 00:40:37.370 align:middle line:84%
They wanted
psychological intimacy.

00:40:37.370 --> 00:40:39.840 align:middle line:84%
He was offering a
different kind of intimacy,

00:40:39.840 --> 00:40:42.170 align:middle line:84%
which is the kind of
intimacy he and I had,

00:40:42.170 --> 00:40:44.120 align:middle line:84%
which is the intimacy
of shared awareness.

00:40:44.120 --> 00:40:46.680 align:middle line:90%


00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:48.290 align:middle line:90%
That kind of thing.

00:40:48.290 --> 00:40:51.620 align:middle line:84%
He didn't get as deep
into psychodynamic stuff.

00:40:51.620 --> 00:40:53.270 align:middle line:84%
I mean, here he
was, a psychologist

00:40:53.270 --> 00:40:55.790 align:middle line:84%
who had created a
very, very highly

00:40:55.790 --> 00:40:59.780 align:middle line:84%
regarded diagnostic
psychological inventory

00:40:59.780 --> 00:41:01.255 align:middle line:90%
for assessing personality.

00:41:01.255 --> 00:41:02.630 align:middle line:84%
The reason he was
so good at that

00:41:02.630 --> 00:41:04.850 align:middle line:84%
is because he was
outside of that.

00:41:04.850 --> 00:41:08.450 align:middle line:84%
That domain or that
plane of consciousness

00:41:08.450 --> 00:41:12.800 align:middle line:84%
didn't engage him, so that
most of the women around him

00:41:12.800 --> 00:41:14.133 align:middle line:90%
were always disappointed.

00:41:14.133 --> 00:41:16.550 align:middle line:84%
>> Now you put the tie, and
then you fold that thing over.

00:41:16.550 --> 00:41:20.230 align:middle line:84%
>> Tim's friendship with
Dick also grew rocky.

00:41:20.230 --> 00:41:23.740 align:middle line:84%
Theirs had been like a
marriage, at least in some ways.

00:41:23.740 --> 00:41:27.010 align:middle line:84%
>> My capacity to be in that
relationship to Timothy,

00:41:27.010 --> 00:41:30.070 align:middle line:84%
part of it, I'm sure,
arises from the fact that

00:41:30.070 --> 00:41:31.210 align:middle line:90%
I'm basically gay.

00:41:31.210 --> 00:41:34.840 align:middle line:84%
And my relation with Timothy
was never physical love.

00:41:34.840 --> 00:41:37.990 align:middle line:84%
But there was a love
affair going on.

00:41:37.990 --> 00:41:39.250 align:middle line:90%
I mean, we loved each other.

00:41:39.250 --> 00:41:41.090 align:middle line:90%
We really loved each other.

00:41:41.090 --> 00:41:45.070 align:middle line:84%
And I became very trustworthy
for Tim to push against,

00:41:45.070 --> 00:41:47.860 align:middle line:84%
to lean on, in a way,
to get further out.

00:41:47.860 --> 00:41:50.920 align:middle line:84%
And Timothy was taking
me out with him.

00:41:50.920 --> 00:41:53.410 align:middle line:84%
Going out with him
wasn't all fun and games.

00:41:53.410 --> 00:41:55.630 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it was extremely scary.

00:41:55.630 --> 00:41:59.770 align:middle line:84%
Because I had grown up in a
family that treasured antiques,

00:41:59.770 --> 00:42:03.040 align:middle line:84%
for example, so that my
apartment in Cambridge,

00:42:03.040 --> 00:42:04.510 align:middle line:84%
when I was a Harvard
professor, was

00:42:04.510 --> 00:42:08.350 align:middle line:84%
full of absolutely beautiful
antiques, highboys.

00:42:08.350 --> 00:42:10.060 align:middle line:84%
And then I moved
to Millbrook where

00:42:10.060 --> 00:42:14.320 align:middle line:84%
it was monkeys, and aardvarks,
and cats, and six dogs,

00:42:14.320 --> 00:42:15.910 align:middle line:90%
and many children.

00:42:15.910 --> 00:42:18.640 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we were in a
63-room house, you know?

00:42:18.640 --> 00:42:21.170 align:middle line:84%
And I watched my
antiques, one by--

00:42:21.170 --> 00:42:24.270 align:middle line:84%
I didn't have the intelligence
to just sell them, you know?

00:42:24.270 --> 00:42:29.390 align:middle line:84%
[LAUGHS] I watched them all just
be destroyed before my eyes.

00:42:29.390 --> 00:42:32.000 align:middle line:84%
It was undercutting
something very deep in me.

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:36.360 align:middle line:90%


00:42:36.360 --> 00:42:39.580 align:middle line:84%
Then, as the years went
on, something very profound

00:42:39.580 --> 00:42:40.380 align:middle line:90%
happened.

00:42:40.380 --> 00:42:44.310 align:middle line:84%
Because I started to
distinguish between visionary

00:42:44.310 --> 00:42:48.180 align:middle line:84%
and revolutionary, and
that Timothy was both.

00:42:48.180 --> 00:42:50.130 align:middle line:90%
And I loved the visionary part.

00:42:50.130 --> 00:42:53.040 align:middle line:84%
And what I saw was that the
revolutionary part of it

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:57.780 align:middle line:84%
was costing so much,
psychically, and financially,

00:42:57.780 --> 00:43:00.030 align:middle line:90%
and socially, and everything.

00:43:00.030 --> 00:43:01.800 align:middle line:90%
We were $50,000 in debt.

00:43:01.800 --> 00:43:04.507 align:middle line:84%
And no matter how hard I
tried, I couldn't pay it off.

00:43:04.507 --> 00:43:06.840 align:middle line:84%
And we were getting further
and further out all the time

00:43:06.840 --> 00:43:08.840 align:middle line:84%
as we got thrown out of
more and more countries.

00:43:08.840 --> 00:43:11.430 align:middle line:84%
I thought, as much
fun as it was,

00:43:11.430 --> 00:43:13.410 align:middle line:84%
now it was no
longer so much fun.

00:43:13.410 --> 00:43:15.870 align:middle line:84%
And the other part of it
was, being in a relationship

00:43:15.870 --> 00:43:18.750 align:middle line:84%
with somebody that
way, ultimately,

00:43:18.750 --> 00:43:21.210 align:middle line:84%
that other part of
you never develops.

00:43:21.210 --> 00:43:23.400 align:middle line:84%
And I realized that I was
a more creative person

00:43:23.400 --> 00:43:25.900 align:middle line:84%
than this situation
was allowing me to be.

00:43:25.900 --> 00:43:27.810 align:middle line:84%
And at that point,
I think that's when

00:43:27.810 --> 00:43:30.180 align:middle line:90%
we started to pull apart.

00:43:30.180 --> 00:43:35.090 align:middle line:84%
>> In the fall of 1965, Richard
Alpert left Millbrook for good.

00:43:35.090 --> 00:43:39.240 align:middle line:84%
The awakenings that psychedelics
provided him never lasted long.

00:43:39.240 --> 00:43:41.340 align:middle line:84%
Alpert and others
hungered for a way

00:43:41.340 --> 00:43:44.190 align:middle line:84%
to maintain and
integrate expanded states

00:43:44.190 --> 00:43:45.690 align:middle line:90%
of consciousness.

00:43:45.690 --> 00:43:49.740 align:middle line:84%
>> Eventually, the world of
mind-manifesting substances

00:43:49.740 --> 00:43:52.680 align:middle line:90%
became more like decoration.

00:43:52.680 --> 00:43:57.120 align:middle line:84%
In this era of the civil rights
and the anti-war movement,

00:43:57.120 --> 00:44:00.390 align:middle line:84%
I realized that, to be
engaged politically,

00:44:00.390 --> 00:44:03.240 align:middle line:84%
I had to also be engaged
with my own mind.

00:44:03.240 --> 00:44:07.770 align:middle line:10%
And I just wanted to really
train my mind be very, very

00:44:07.770 --> 00:44:09.960 align:middle line:10%
stable and to be
able to perceive

00:44:09.960 --> 00:44:15.910 align:middle line:10%
my own mental continuum clearly
and not have it so decorated.

00:44:15.910 --> 00:44:19.090 align:middle line:84%
>> As Alpert was leaving, Leary
began a new relationship with

00:44:19.090 --> 00:44:20.680 align:middle line:90%
Rosemary Woodruff.

00:44:20.680 --> 00:44:22.660 align:middle line:84%
They closed up the
house at Millbrook

00:44:22.660 --> 00:44:26.170 align:middle line:84%
and began a trip to Mexico with
Tim's children, Susan and Jack.

00:44:26.170 --> 00:44:28.680 align:middle line:90%


00:44:28.680 --> 00:44:31.340 align:middle line:84%
But at the border
crossing in Laredo, Texas,

00:44:31.340 --> 00:44:33.950 align:middle line:84%
they were arrested for the
possession of less than half

00:44:33.950 --> 00:44:37.550 align:middle line:84%
an ounce of marijuana,
for which Leary received

00:44:37.550 --> 00:44:42.030 align:middle line:90%
a jail sentence of 30 years.

00:44:42.030 --> 00:44:46.280 align:middle line:84%
They returned to Millbrook and
began fighting the conviction.

00:44:46.280 --> 00:44:48.920 align:middle line:84%
Ultimately, the Supreme Court
overturned the sentence.

00:44:48.920 --> 00:44:52.670 align:middle line:84%
But Nixon was not satisfied
with that outcome.

00:44:52.670 --> 00:44:55.370 align:middle line:84%
Leary was indeed
later jailed, but

00:44:55.370 --> 00:44:57.950 align:middle line:84%
for interstate transportation,
not possession.

00:44:57.950 --> 00:45:00.200 align:middle line:84%
>> You're not going to solve
these problems by putting

00:45:00.200 --> 00:45:03.380 align:middle line:84%
leading scientists like myself
in jail for 30 or 40-year

00:45:03.380 --> 00:45:07.730 align:middle line:84%
prison terms for doing nothing
more than attempting to use

00:45:07.730 --> 00:45:11.200 align:middle line:84%
and understand these new forms
of energy for which yet there

00:45:11.200 --> 00:45:14.300 align:middle line:84%
is no evidence that we've
done any damage to society

00:45:14.300 --> 00:45:17.210 align:middle line:84%
or to ourselves or
to other people.

00:45:17.210 --> 00:45:20.510 align:middle line:84%
>> In 1966, drug use of
all kinds was on the rise

00:45:20.510 --> 00:45:22.590 align:middle line:90%
in America.

00:45:22.590 --> 00:45:24.450 align:middle line:84%
Even though his views
were controversial,

00:45:24.450 --> 00:45:27.640 align:middle line:84%
Leary was invited to
testify before Congress.

00:45:27.640 --> 00:45:31.330 align:middle line:84%
>> We have been told today and
we read in the papers reports

00:45:31.330 --> 00:45:35.090 align:middle line:84%
from sociologists that
from between 15% to 50%--

00:45:35.090 --> 00:45:39.650 align:middle line:84%
and in some cases, up to 65% and
70% of our college students--

00:45:39.650 --> 00:45:43.100 align:middle line:84%
are experimenting with these
mind-opening chemicals.

00:45:43.100 --> 00:45:45.980 align:middle line:10%
And I recommend, respectfully,
to this committee

00:45:45.980 --> 00:45:49.190 align:middle line:10%
that you consider
legislation which

00:45:49.190 --> 00:45:52.370 align:middle line:10%
will license responsible
adults to use

00:45:52.370 --> 00:45:55.560 align:middle line:10%
these drugs for
serious purposes,

00:45:55.560 --> 00:45:58.700 align:middle line:10%
such as spiritual growth,
the pursuit of knowledge,

00:45:58.700 --> 00:46:02.060 align:middle line:10%
or in their own
personal development.

00:46:02.060 --> 00:46:06.050 align:middle line:84%
To obtain such a license,
the applicant, I think,

00:46:06.050 --> 00:46:09.230 align:middle line:84%
should have to meet
physical, intellectual,

00:46:09.230 --> 00:46:11.030 align:middle line:90%
and emotional criteria.

00:46:11.030 --> 00:46:14.940 align:middle line:84%
>> Your testimony I
understand extremely clearly.

00:46:14.940 --> 00:46:17.210 align:middle line:84%
And it's coming more
clear now that you

00:46:17.210 --> 00:46:19.640 align:middle line:84%
feel that there shouldn't
be an indiscriminate--

00:46:19.640 --> 00:46:21.380 align:middle line:84%
indiscriminate
possession is something

00:46:21.380 --> 00:46:24.340 align:middle line:90%
that you do not support.

00:46:24.340 --> 00:46:27.050 align:middle line:84%
>> For six years, sir, I
have been indiscriminate use.

00:46:27.050 --> 00:46:28.210 align:middle line:90%
>> I know.

00:46:28.210 --> 00:46:30.740 align:middle line:90%
Indiscriminate use, all right.

00:46:30.740 --> 00:46:33.890 align:middle line:10%
>> And he felt very strongly
that he would be able

00:46:33.890 --> 00:46:38.270 align:middle line:10%
to convince Congress that
psychotropic drugs be given

00:46:38.270 --> 00:46:41.180 align:middle line:10%
over to the medical profession
for healing purposes.

00:46:41.180 --> 00:46:41.980 align:middle line:90%
[KNOCKING]

00:46:41.980 --> 00:46:43.070 align:middle line:90%
>> Police officer.

00:46:43.070 --> 00:46:45.470 align:middle line:90%
Open the door.

00:46:45.470 --> 00:46:49.370 align:middle line:84%
>> And he knew that, the minute
they decided to make this a law

00:46:49.370 --> 00:46:53.930 align:middle line:84%
enforcement issue, it
would be everywhere.

00:46:53.930 --> 00:46:56.390 align:middle line:90%
There would be no stopping it.

00:46:56.390 --> 00:46:59.300 align:middle line:84%
Everybody would be
able to get hold of it.

00:46:59.300 --> 00:47:01.070 align:middle line:90%
That was terrible for him.

00:47:01.070 --> 00:47:05.770 align:middle line:84%
That's where he developed
a very strong rebel

00:47:05.770 --> 00:47:09.510 align:middle line:90%
side towards the government.

00:47:09.510 --> 00:47:12.270 align:middle line:84%
>> As Leary continued fighting
the government and the Texas

00:47:12.270 --> 00:47:17.640 align:middle line:84%
courts, the direction of Richard
Alpert's life changed forever.

00:47:17.640 --> 00:47:23.000 align:middle line:84%
He had left the country in
1967 on a trip through Asia.

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:25.490 align:middle line:84%
One day, in Nepal, he
met a young Westerner

00:47:25.490 --> 00:47:28.220 align:middle line:84%
who had adopted the ways of
the Indian ascetics known

00:47:28.220 --> 00:47:30.050 align:middle line:90%
as sadhus.

00:47:30.050 --> 00:47:34.650 align:middle line:84%
Bhagavan Das seemed to embody
what Richard was looking for.

00:47:34.650 --> 00:47:36.920 align:middle line:10%
So he abandoned his
first-class junket,

00:47:36.920 --> 00:47:41.950 align:middle line:10%
and, together, they descended
barefoot into India.

00:47:41.950 --> 00:47:43.960 align:middle line:10%
Before long, Richard
was introduced

00:47:43.960 --> 00:47:45.850 align:middle line:10%
to the Indian saint
who would become

00:47:45.850 --> 00:47:50.620 align:middle line:10%
his guru, Neem Karoli Baba,
known to his followers

00:47:50.620 --> 00:47:53.360 align:middle line:10%
as Maharaj-ji.

00:47:53.360 --> 00:47:57.050 align:middle line:84%
Maharaj-ji gave Richard his
spiritual name, Ram Dass,

00:47:57.050 --> 00:48:00.140 align:middle line:90%
which means "servant of God."

00:48:00.140 --> 00:48:04.640 align:middle line:84%
>> My guru is about
a 70-year-old man.

00:48:04.640 --> 00:48:06.757 align:middle line:84%
I don't know anything
about him, really.

00:48:06.757 --> 00:48:09.090 align:middle line:84%
I don't even know that he
exists, to tell you the truth.

00:48:09.090 --> 00:48:10.550 align:middle line:84%
But it seemed to
me that there was

00:48:10.550 --> 00:48:11.805 align:middle line:90%
a little old man in a blanket.

00:48:11.805 --> 00:48:14.180 align:middle line:84%
And when I looked at him, the
first time I looked at him,

00:48:14.180 --> 00:48:16.628 align:middle line:84%
I thought I wasn't
going to be hustled.

00:48:16.628 --> 00:48:18.920 align:middle line:84%
And the second time I looked
at him, all I wanted to do

00:48:18.920 --> 00:48:21.030 align:middle line:90%
was touch his feet.

00:48:21.030 --> 00:48:29.420 align:middle line:84%
I looked up, and he was looking
at me with unconditional love.

00:48:29.420 --> 00:48:33.920 align:middle line:84%
And I had never been looked
at with unconditional love

00:48:33.920 --> 00:48:35.980 align:middle line:90%
by anybody.

00:48:35.980 --> 00:48:38.930 align:middle line:90%
I felt love.

00:48:38.930 --> 00:48:41.150 align:middle line:90%
I felt love.

00:48:41.150 --> 00:48:47.710 align:middle line:84%
And I felt something
happening in my heart.

00:48:47.710 --> 00:48:50.830 align:middle line:84%
>> Ram Dass studied yoga and
meditation before returning

00:48:50.830 --> 00:48:53.950 align:middle line:90%
to America a changed man

00:48:53.950 --> 00:48:57.820 align:middle line:84%
>> Timothy trained me in
the beginning of my escape.

00:48:57.820 --> 00:49:00.340 align:middle line:84%
And Maharaj-ji then
took over, really.

00:49:00.340 --> 00:49:03.720 align:middle line:84%
I see them as my two
powerful teachers in escape.

00:49:03.720 --> 00:49:07.090 align:middle line:90%


00:49:07.090 --> 00:49:08.200 align:middle line:90%
>> And he comes back.

00:49:08.200 --> 00:49:12.490 align:middle line:84%
And he's maybe 80
pounds lighter.

00:49:12.490 --> 00:49:14.920 align:middle line:84%
And he's putting on a
lot of holy man airs

00:49:14.920 --> 00:49:17.980 align:middle line:84%
that are particularly
grating, having seen him

00:49:17.980 --> 00:49:20.460 align:middle line:90%
in his previous manifestation.

00:49:20.460 --> 00:49:25.870 align:middle line:84%
And I'm thinking,
same guy, new shtick.

00:49:25.870 --> 00:49:29.260 align:middle line:84%
>> Encouraged by Maharaj-ji,
Ram Dass explored his Indian

00:49:29.260 --> 00:49:32.330 align:middle line:84%
awakenings in the
book "Be Here Now,"

00:49:32.330 --> 00:49:34.760 align:middle line:84%
which became a manual for
spiritual seekers throughout

00:49:34.760 --> 00:49:35.560 align:middle line:90%
the world.

00:49:35.560 --> 00:49:39.450 align:middle line:90%


00:49:39.450 --> 00:49:41.840 align:middle line:10%
It was first published
in 1971, hand-stamped

00:49:41.840 --> 00:49:47.190 align:middle line:10%
and inked at the Lama
Foundation in New Mexico.

00:49:47.190 --> 00:49:50.250 align:middle line:10%
Originally a limited edition
with hand-stitched pages,

00:49:50.250 --> 00:49:54.000 align:middle line:10%
it is now in its 43rd printing.

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:56.160 align:middle line:90%
>> "Be Here Now" was seminal.

00:49:56.160 --> 00:49:57.150 align:middle line:90%
It's still seminal.

00:49:57.150 --> 00:49:59.485 align:middle line:84%
It's still opening up
young people's minds.

00:49:59.485 --> 00:50:03.540 align:middle line:84%
They get that book, and it does
what it did to us so long ago.

00:50:03.540 --> 00:50:06.320 align:middle line:90%
It's amazing.

00:50:06.320 --> 00:50:09.160 align:middle line:84%
Ram Dass was a bridge
between east and west

00:50:09.160 --> 00:50:15.010 align:middle line:84%
and was a major person to open
this gateway to Eastern wisdom

00:50:15.010 --> 00:50:17.950 align:middle line:90%
to Western culture.

00:50:17.950 --> 00:50:19.610 align:middle line:90%
>> You can tell me.

00:50:19.610 --> 00:50:21.890 align:middle line:90%
Where'd "Be Here Now" come from?

00:50:21.890 --> 00:50:22.790 align:middle line:90%
That was you.

00:50:22.790 --> 00:50:23.590 align:middle line:90%
>> "Be Here Now?"

00:50:23.590 --> 00:50:24.610 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:50:24.610 --> 00:50:26.027 align:middle line:84%
You've heard of
that, haven't you?

00:50:26.027 --> 00:50:26.870 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, yeah.

00:50:26.870 --> 00:50:27.880 align:middle line:90%
>> You invented that.

00:50:27.880 --> 00:50:30.790 align:middle line:84%
>> But it was really
actually Bhagavan Das.

00:50:30.790 --> 00:50:34.630 align:middle line:84%
Every time my mind would go
off into my Jewish neuroticism,

00:50:34.630 --> 00:50:38.710 align:middle line:84%
he'd say, look, just come
back here, and be here now.

00:50:38.710 --> 00:50:44.510 align:middle line:84%
So I took it as a title,
but he used to say it to me.

00:50:44.510 --> 00:50:47.840 align:middle line:84%
>> Since then, Ram Dass has
traveled and taught widely,

00:50:47.840 --> 00:50:51.240 align:middle line:84%
written numerous books, and,
putting spirit into action,

00:50:51.240 --> 00:50:53.340 align:middle line:84%
co-founded service
organizations.

00:50:53.340 --> 00:50:58.690 align:middle line:90%


00:50:58.690 --> 00:51:01.210 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm going to run for the
governorship of the state

00:51:01.210 --> 00:51:02.830 align:middle line:90%
of California.

00:51:02.830 --> 00:51:06.370 align:middle line:10%
>> In 1968, Leary was
again busted for pot,

00:51:06.370 --> 00:51:09.220 align:middle line:10%
this time by the California
State Police during his

00:51:09.220 --> 00:51:12.250 align:middle line:10%
abortive run for governor
against the incumbent Ronald

00:51:12.250 --> 00:51:13.640 align:middle line:10%
Reagan.

00:51:13.640 --> 00:51:16.000 align:middle line:84%
He had the support of
people like John Lennon,

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:18.790 align:middle line:84%
who wrote the Beatles tune "Come
Together" for the campaign.

00:51:18.790 --> 00:51:20.415 align:middle line:84%
[MUSIC - THE BEATLES, "COME
 TOGETHER"]

00:51:20.415 --> 00:51:24.465 align:middle line:84%
>> (SINGING) Come together
right now over me.

00:51:24.465 --> 00:51:27.630 align:middle line:10%
>> Named the most dangerous man
in America by President Richard

00:51:27.630 --> 00:51:31.590 align:middle line:10%
Nixon, Leary insisted the
marijuana found in his car had

00:51:31.590 --> 00:51:32.430 align:middle line:10%
been planted.

00:51:32.430 --> 00:51:34.020 align:middle line:10%
>> One evening, I
was in a parked car.

00:51:34.020 --> 00:51:35.900 align:middle line:10%
And a policeman
came up to the car

00:51:35.900 --> 00:51:38.270 align:middle line:10%
and opened the door
against my wishes.

00:51:38.270 --> 00:51:40.530 align:middle line:84%
He made a pass at the
ash tray and said,

00:51:40.530 --> 00:51:42.078 align:middle line:90%
you're under arrest for--

00:51:42.078 --> 00:51:42.942 align:middle line:90%
I said, for what?

00:51:42.942 --> 00:51:43.900 align:middle line:90%
He said, for marijuana.

00:51:43.900 --> 00:51:44.805 align:middle line:90%
What marijuana?

00:51:44.805 --> 00:51:49.600 align:middle line:84%
He reached in his
pocket and pulled out

00:51:49.600 --> 00:51:51.820 align:middle line:84%
two joints I'd never seen
before-- half joints.

00:51:51.820 --> 00:51:55.215 align:middle line:84%
And then it was like,
you're under arrests.

00:51:55.215 --> 00:51:56.190 align:middle line:90%
[CELL DOORS SLAMMING]

00:51:56.190 --> 00:51:58.440 align:middle line:84%
>> He was finally
jailed in 1970,

00:51:58.440 --> 00:52:02.430 align:middle line:84%
one of the first casualties
of the war on drugs.

00:52:02.430 --> 00:52:05.040 align:middle line:10%
But when he was given the
very personality assessment

00:52:05.040 --> 00:52:08.220 align:middle line:10%
he had himself devised
at Berkeley in the 1950s,

00:52:08.220 --> 00:52:11.910 align:middle line:10%
he got himself assigned to
a minimum security prison.

00:52:11.910 --> 00:52:16.320 align:middle line:10%
Then he escaped, with the aid
of the Weather Underground

00:52:16.320 --> 00:52:17.790 align:middle line:10%
and the Black Panthers.

00:52:17.790 --> 00:52:19.650 align:middle line:90%
>> Comment on your plans now.

00:52:19.650 --> 00:52:22.220 align:middle line:84%
>> My plans are to work
with the Black Panther Party

00:52:22.220 --> 00:52:24.420 align:middle line:84%
for the overthrow of
the American government.

00:52:24.420 --> 00:52:29.140 align:middle line:10%
>> When we crossed
paths in Algeria,

00:52:29.140 --> 00:52:31.650 align:middle line:10%
he didn't look like he
was having that much fun.

00:52:31.650 --> 00:52:34.280 align:middle line:10%
Eldridge Cleaver looked
definitely distressed.

00:52:34.280 --> 00:52:37.180 align:middle line:84%
And it didn't look like they
were enjoying each other.

00:52:37.180 --> 00:52:40.470 align:middle line:84%
But I think Tim played
with every edge.

00:52:40.470 --> 00:52:45.900 align:middle line:84%
>> He spoke about his life
in terms of being imprisoned

00:52:45.900 --> 00:52:46.860 align:middle line:90%
and escaping.

00:52:46.860 --> 00:52:49.240 align:middle line:10%
So he said that
he was in prison,

00:52:49.240 --> 00:52:51.480 align:middle line:10%
and he escaped, and
he went to Algeria

00:52:51.480 --> 00:52:53.010 align:middle line:10%
with his wife, Rosemary.

00:52:53.010 --> 00:52:55.710 align:middle line:10%
And once again,
he was in prison,

00:52:55.710 --> 00:52:58.530 align:middle line:10%
and he needed to escape.

00:52:58.530 --> 00:53:00.620 align:middle line:90%
And then he went to Switzerland.

00:53:00.620 --> 00:53:03.180 align:middle line:84%
And once again, instead
of being imprisoned

00:53:03.180 --> 00:53:05.610 align:middle line:84%
by Eldridge Cleaver
and his politics,

00:53:05.610 --> 00:53:10.620 align:middle line:84%
then he was imprisoned by a
gangster and his machinations.

00:53:10.620 --> 00:53:16.710 align:middle line:84%
Rosemary left him while
they were in Switzerland.

00:53:16.710 --> 00:53:18.540 align:middle line:84%
I think he was very
sad about that.

00:53:18.540 --> 00:53:22.330 align:middle line:84%
And I think he
absolutely adored her.

00:53:22.330 --> 00:53:25.780 align:middle line:84%
Who Timothy Leary was
for me, in the beginning,

00:53:25.780 --> 00:53:28.198 align:middle line:84%
he was just a song
of the Moody Blues.

00:53:28.198 --> 00:53:30.115 align:middle line:84%
[MUSIC - THE MOODY BLUES,
 "LEGEND OF A MIND"]

00:53:30.115 --> 00:53:33.982 align:middle line:84%
>> (SINGING) Timothy
Leary's dead.

00:53:33.982 --> 00:53:39.898 align:middle line:84%
No, no, he's
outside, looking in.

00:53:39.898 --> 00:53:44.115 align:middle line:90%


00:53:44.115 --> 00:53:48.810 align:middle line:84%
>> Little by little, I sort of
got this romantic image that

00:53:48.810 --> 00:53:53.850 align:middle line:84%
this Timothy Leary might
be the king of outlaws.

00:53:53.850 --> 00:53:58.530 align:middle line:84%
Through a series of
extraordinary coincidences,

00:53:58.530 --> 00:54:01.470 align:middle line:84%
I met Timothy Leary
in Switzerland

00:54:01.470 --> 00:54:06.420 align:middle line:84%
and found out that he was
a fugitive from prison.

00:54:06.420 --> 00:54:12.900 align:middle line:84%
I was 26 years old, and I
found that very exciting.

00:54:12.900 --> 00:54:16.770 align:middle line:84%
It felt like it was my
destiny to meet him.

00:54:16.770 --> 00:54:22.560 align:middle line:84%
And I was ready for
anything with him.

00:54:22.560 --> 00:54:26.040 align:middle line:84%
We flew to Afghanistan
from Vienna.

00:54:26.040 --> 00:54:29.900 align:middle line:10%
When we got to the
airport in Afghanistan,

00:54:29.900 --> 00:54:32.340 align:middle line:10%
an attache at the
American embassy

00:54:32.340 --> 00:54:36.540 align:middle line:10%
stole our passports
out of Timothy's hands,

00:54:36.540 --> 00:54:39.325 align:middle line:10%
and this incredible
ordeal started.

00:54:39.325 --> 00:54:42.490 align:middle line:90%


00:54:42.490 --> 00:54:45.610 align:middle line:84%
I was taken with him
back to California,

00:54:45.610 --> 00:54:46.510 align:middle line:90%
where I'd never been.

00:54:46.510 --> 00:54:49.310 align:middle line:90%


00:54:49.310 --> 00:54:53.570 align:middle line:84%
It was a perfect
PR coup for Nixon.

00:54:53.570 --> 00:54:56.450 align:middle line:84%
Two days before
the inauguration,

00:54:56.450 --> 00:55:00.080 align:middle line:84%
we got brought back in front
of hundreds of journalists.

00:55:00.080 --> 00:55:02.090 align:middle line:90%
So Nixon had the front page--

00:55:02.090 --> 00:55:04.120 align:middle line:84%
Timothy Leary
brought into custody.

00:55:04.120 --> 00:55:06.230 align:middle line:90%
[GAVEL BANGING]

00:55:06.230 --> 00:55:08.700 align:middle line:84%
He was in Folsom
Prison for a year.

00:55:08.700 --> 00:55:12.460 align:middle line:10%
[CELL DOOR SLAMMING]

00:55:12.460 --> 00:55:15.080 align:middle line:84%
>> For those of
you who know him,

00:55:15.080 --> 00:55:17.390 align:middle line:90%
he's relaxed and he looks well.

00:55:17.390 --> 00:55:21.470 align:middle line:84%
But behind the camera sits the
warden, the assistant warden,

00:55:21.470 --> 00:55:25.220 align:middle line:84%
and probably the
captain of the guard.

00:55:25.220 --> 00:55:27.730 align:middle line:84%
I am Joanna Leary, and
I'd like to see him out

00:55:27.730 --> 00:55:29.450 align:middle line:90%
of here as quick as possible.

00:55:29.450 --> 00:55:30.950 align:middle line:84%
>> What do you think
of your future?

00:55:30.950 --> 00:55:33.200 align:middle line:84%
Do you think you're going
to walk out of Folsom Prison

00:55:33.200 --> 00:55:34.042 align:middle line:90%
a free man one day?

00:55:34.042 --> 00:55:36.500 align:middle line:84%
>> I think my future is very
interconnected with the future

00:55:36.500 --> 00:55:37.420 align:middle line:90%
of this country.

00:55:37.420 --> 00:55:40.670 align:middle line:84%
You just can't keep your
philosophers in prison.

00:55:40.670 --> 00:55:43.400 align:middle line:84%
If I am kept in
prison, it's going

00:55:43.400 --> 00:55:46.690 align:middle line:84%
to be a very bad symptom
for freedom, and for hope,

00:55:46.690 --> 00:55:47.780 align:middle line:90%
and for union.

00:55:47.780 --> 00:55:51.490 align:middle line:90%


00:55:51.490 --> 00:55:56.650 align:middle line:84%
>> I began to see this man come
out of his solitary confinement

00:55:56.650 --> 00:56:02.710 align:middle line:84%
cell, somewhat
confused, very red eyes.

00:56:02.710 --> 00:56:08.170 align:middle line:84%
He told me that they probably
fed him drugs in the food

00:56:08.170 --> 00:56:10.140 align:middle line:90%
they were giving him.

00:56:10.140 --> 00:56:16.470 align:middle line:84%
They let me visit him when
he was in a padded cell,

00:56:16.470 --> 00:56:18.860 align:middle line:90%
using a straitjacket.

00:56:18.860 --> 00:56:20.630 align:middle line:90%
His head was shaved.

00:56:20.630 --> 00:56:22.790 align:middle line:84%
And he began to
change in the sense

00:56:22.790 --> 00:56:25.190 align:middle line:84%
that there was less
and less and less

00:56:25.190 --> 00:56:29.030 align:middle line:90%
of Timothy Leary on the outside.

00:56:29.030 --> 00:56:33.450 align:middle line:10%
Isolation is not only to
keep somebody in a box,

00:56:33.450 --> 00:56:36.650 align:middle line:10%
but it's so they
unlearn to communicate

00:56:36.650 --> 00:56:39.340 align:middle line:10%
with the outside world.

00:56:39.340 --> 00:56:42.550 align:middle line:10%
>> Criminalizing use
and possession of drugs

00:56:42.550 --> 00:56:43.460 align:middle line:10%
doesn't work.

00:56:43.460 --> 00:56:45.830 align:middle line:90%
And it makes everything worse.

00:56:45.830 --> 00:56:49.090 align:middle line:84%
I don't think we can suddenly
legalize things overnight.

00:56:49.090 --> 00:56:54.430 align:middle line:84%
I believe in education as the
key to rational drug policy.

00:56:54.430 --> 00:56:57.400 align:middle line:10%
And that means being honest
about their positive effects as

00:56:57.400 --> 00:57:00.970 align:middle line:10%
well as negative effects, being
honest about the drugs whose

00:57:00.970 --> 00:57:03.100 align:middle line:10%
use we not only
tolerate, but promote,

00:57:03.100 --> 00:57:07.060 align:middle line:10%
like alcohol and tobacco,
and that we make money from,

00:57:07.060 --> 00:57:08.840 align:middle line:10%
our government makes money from.

00:57:08.840 --> 00:57:14.350 align:middle line:84%
So it's real education,
truthful education.

00:57:14.350 --> 00:57:18.220 align:middle line:84%
And I think it has to be
at all levels of society.

00:57:18.220 --> 00:57:21.910 align:middle line:10%
Timothy decided to turn
state and federal evidence

00:57:21.910 --> 00:57:24.750 align:middle line:10%
so he would get out of prison.

00:57:24.750 --> 00:57:28.350 align:middle line:84%
The next morning, the
feds came and said,

00:57:28.350 --> 00:57:35.110 align:middle line:84%
we've received news that people
want to kill you, both of you.

00:57:35.110 --> 00:57:39.900 align:middle line:84%
And so you have to go into the
Witness Protection Program.

00:57:39.900 --> 00:57:44.240 align:middle line:84%
Timothy insisted that
they bring us to Santa Fe.

00:57:44.240 --> 00:57:49.595 align:middle line:84%
Our names were changed
to James and Nora Joyce.

00:57:49.595 --> 00:57:54.350 align:middle line:84%
We were two drunks,
lost in the wilderness,

00:57:54.350 --> 00:57:57.720 align:middle line:90%
trying to encounter each other.

00:57:57.720 --> 00:58:05.860 align:middle line:84%
The loneliness, the
separation, the isolation

00:58:05.860 --> 00:58:12.140 align:middle line:84%
had driven my alcoholism
and my drug addiction

00:58:12.140 --> 00:58:15.330 align:middle line:90%
to an excruciating place.

00:58:15.330 --> 00:58:17.640 align:middle line:90%
And so we fought a lot.

00:58:17.640 --> 00:58:20.690 align:middle line:90%
We had both suffered so much.

00:58:20.690 --> 00:58:23.140 align:middle line:10%
And from where I
look at it right now,

00:58:23.140 --> 00:58:28.660 align:middle line:10%
I think that the right move
for him was to blame me.

00:58:28.660 --> 00:58:34.190 align:middle line:90%


00:58:34.190 --> 00:58:37.870 align:middle line:84%
>> In the end, Leary spent
almost four years in jail,

00:58:37.870 --> 00:58:41.450 align:middle line:84%
of which two and a half were
in solitary confinement.

00:58:41.450 --> 00:58:43.710 align:middle line:10%
But no matter how dark
the circumstances,

00:58:43.710 --> 00:58:46.370 align:middle line:10%
he always remembered that
Marshall McLuhan had advised

00:58:46.370 --> 00:58:51.530 align:middle line:10%
him to wave reassuringly,
radiate courage,

00:58:51.530 --> 00:58:55.340 align:middle line:10%
and you must be
known for your smile.

00:58:55.340 --> 00:58:58.220 align:middle line:10%
>> I've been in 40 jails
in four continents.

00:58:58.220 --> 00:59:03.202 align:middle line:10%
>> [LAUGHS] I haven't
even been busted yet.

00:59:03.202 --> 00:59:06.818 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:59:06.818 --> 00:59:11.170 align:middle line:10%
>> The proliferation of LSD,
and psychedelics, and marijuana,

00:59:11.170 --> 00:59:15.040 align:middle line:10%
even, within popular
culture was a Pandora's box.

00:59:15.040 --> 00:59:19.000 align:middle line:10%
The second youth
culture got ahold of it,

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:22.402 align:middle line:10%
it exploded, much greater
than anybody knew it would,

00:59:22.402 --> 00:59:23.860 align:middle line:10%
much greater than
he knew it would.

00:59:23.860 --> 00:59:26.680 align:middle line:84%
>> Tim really was
naive, innocent.

00:59:26.680 --> 00:59:30.160 align:middle line:84%
He did not anticipate
the kind of reaction.

00:59:30.160 --> 00:59:32.710 align:middle line:84%
>> Nevertheless, Leary
is often solely blamed

00:59:32.710 --> 00:59:35.550 align:middle line:84%
for their popularization
and misuse.

00:59:35.550 --> 00:59:42.620 align:middle line:10%
>> As that poisonous, evil man,
Dr. Timothy Leary, has said,

00:59:42.620 --> 00:59:45.620 align:middle line:10%
it is a way to turn on,
tune in, and drop out.

00:59:45.620 --> 00:59:48.800 align:middle line:84%
>> People say, you ruined
an entire generation.

00:59:48.800 --> 00:59:50.910 align:middle line:84%
And I go, but that's
72 million people.

00:59:50.910 --> 00:59:51.710 align:middle line:90%
They said, yeah.

00:59:51.710 --> 00:59:53.150 align:middle line:90%
They say, don't you feel regret?

00:59:53.150 --> 00:59:55.390 align:middle line:84%
And I say, well,
one thing I feel--

00:59:55.390 --> 00:59:57.370 align:middle line:84%
only 100,000 of
them had the decency

00:59:57.370 --> 00:59:59.360 align:middle line:84%
to thank me for
ruining their past.

00:59:59.360 --> 01:00:03.320 align:middle line:90%
>> [LAUGHS]

01:00:03.320 --> 01:00:07.280 align:middle line:90%


01:00:07.280 --> 01:00:13.740 align:middle line:84%
>> Turn on to the internal
neurological energy.

01:00:13.740 --> 01:00:17.280 align:middle line:84%
"Tune in" means to harness
up the new revelation

01:00:17.280 --> 01:00:20.370 align:middle line:90%
and energy in your life.

01:00:20.370 --> 01:00:23.610 align:middle line:84%
And drop out-- now this may
sound reckless advice today,

01:00:23.610 --> 01:00:26.040 align:middle line:84%
but it's the oldest
advice that philosophers

01:00:26.040 --> 01:00:27.710 align:middle line:84%
and religious leaders
have passed on.

01:00:27.710 --> 01:00:28.550 align:middle line:90%
Detach.

01:00:28.550 --> 01:00:29.430 align:middle line:90%
Drop out.

01:00:29.430 --> 01:00:30.930 align:middle line:90%
Find what's within.

01:00:30.930 --> 01:00:33.645 align:middle line:90%
Turn on, tune in, and drop out.

01:00:33.645 --> 01:00:36.890 align:middle line:90%
And I stand by that statement.

01:00:36.890 --> 01:00:40.770 align:middle line:90%
[CHANTING]

01:00:40.770 --> 01:00:43.200 align:middle line:90%


01:00:43.200 --> 01:00:45.750 align:middle line:84%
>> Over time, Leary
was dismissive of Dick

01:00:45.750 --> 01:00:49.020 align:middle line:84%
Alpert's spiritual journey,
which he saw as his merely

01:00:49.020 --> 01:00:53.340 align:middle line:84%
playing lieutenant to yet
another prophetic master.

01:00:53.340 --> 01:00:56.610 align:middle line:84%
>> Leary did not
like gurus, period.

01:00:56.610 --> 01:01:00.570 align:middle line:10%
>> Timothy seemed quite
comfortable with the metaphors

01:01:00.570 --> 01:01:02.860 align:middle line:10%
of the religious traditions.

01:01:02.860 --> 01:01:06.270 align:middle line:84%
But later, those became grist
for the mill of his revolution

01:01:06.270 --> 01:01:07.110 align:middle line:90%
also.

01:01:07.110 --> 01:01:11.130 align:middle line:84%
And he treated me like sort of
an old-fashioned type person.

01:01:11.130 --> 01:01:14.040 align:middle line:84%
>> Once Leary's long struggle
with the FBI and the Justice

01:01:14.040 --> 01:01:17.550 align:middle line:84%
Department was concluded, he
settled in Los Angeles with his

01:01:17.550 --> 01:01:21.360 align:middle line:84%
fifth wife, Barbara Chase,
and her son Zachary.

01:01:21.360 --> 01:01:24.450 align:middle line:84%
>> Timothy Leary married my
mother when I was four years

01:01:24.450 --> 01:01:25.330 align:middle line:90%
old.

01:01:25.330 --> 01:01:29.220 align:middle line:84%
And he was the father who
raised me from ages four

01:01:29.220 --> 01:01:35.710 align:middle line:84%
until 22, until he died
when I was 22 years old.

01:01:35.710 --> 01:01:38.190 align:middle line:84%
So I lived with
him for 17 years.

01:01:38.190 --> 01:01:41.250 align:middle line:84%
And somebody pointed
out to me once

01:01:41.250 --> 01:01:43.590 align:middle line:84%
that I have the
great distinction

01:01:43.590 --> 01:01:48.270 align:middle line:84%
of living with him longer
than anybody else did, ever.

01:01:48.270 --> 01:01:52.650 align:middle line:84%
So he was just a great, very
kind of standard white picket

01:01:52.650 --> 01:01:54.767 align:middle line:90%
fence father with me.

01:01:54.767 --> 01:01:56.100 align:middle line:90%
And most people don't know that.

01:01:56.100 --> 01:01:58.890 align:middle line:84%
And when I tell people that,
it's really a surprise.

01:01:58.890 --> 01:02:00.450 align:middle line:84%
He took me to Little
League practice.

01:02:00.450 --> 01:02:02.640 align:middle line:84%
He played baseball
with me in the yard.

01:02:02.640 --> 01:02:04.640 align:middle line:84%
We went to Dodger
games all the time.

01:02:04.640 --> 01:02:06.960 align:middle line:90%
He made sure I did my homework.

01:02:06.960 --> 01:02:09.500 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it was
shockingly normal.

01:02:09.500 --> 01:02:12.920 align:middle line:90%


01:02:12.920 --> 01:02:14.840 align:middle line:84%
>> After some years
of estrangement,

01:02:14.840 --> 01:02:18.710 align:middle line:84%
Leary and Ram Dass's love for
each other as mythic explorers

01:02:18.710 --> 01:02:20.380 align:middle line:90%
guided their reconnection.

01:02:20.380 --> 01:02:23.090 align:middle line:84%
>> The last 20 years
have been remarkable.

01:02:23.090 --> 01:02:26.520 align:middle line:84%
They have put us
through the changes.

01:02:26.520 --> 01:02:28.390 align:middle line:84%
And we've put them
through some changes.

01:02:28.390 --> 01:02:30.070 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

01:02:30.070 --> 01:02:33.520 align:middle line:84%
>> He didn't ask me for
legitimacy of his life,

01:02:33.520 --> 01:02:36.820 align:middle line:84%
and I didn't ask him
for legitimacy of mine.

01:02:36.820 --> 01:02:39.070 align:middle line:84%
That allowed a new
kind of respect

01:02:39.070 --> 01:02:41.930 align:middle line:84%
to emerge between us,
which was interesting.

01:02:41.930 --> 01:02:44.170 align:middle line:84%
It was a respect that
honored our differences,

01:02:44.170 --> 01:02:48.600 align:middle line:84%
rather than the adventure
of sharing an idea.

01:02:48.600 --> 01:02:52.920 align:middle line:84%
And I really felt that Timothy
really respected me at the end.

01:02:52.920 --> 01:02:54.170 align:middle line:90%
And I certainly respected him.

01:02:54.170 --> 01:03:07.830 align:middle line:90%


01:03:07.830 --> 01:03:10.610 align:middle line:84%
>> The question of
"am I afraid to die"

01:03:10.610 --> 01:03:13.347 align:middle line:84%
is something that I
actually live with everyday.

01:03:13.347 --> 01:03:14.930 align:middle line:84%
>> I think everybody
is afraid to die.

01:03:14.930 --> 01:03:17.950 align:middle line:84%
The question is, how do
you deal with the fear?

01:03:17.950 --> 01:03:19.760 align:middle line:90%
>> I like being alive.

01:03:19.760 --> 01:03:21.370 align:middle line:90%
I like this incarnation.

01:03:21.370 --> 01:03:22.550 align:middle line:90%
I'm attached to it.

01:03:22.550 --> 01:03:24.980 align:middle line:84%
>> If I weren't afraid to
die, I would not be taking it

01:03:24.980 --> 01:03:25.790 align:middle line:90%
seriously.

01:03:25.790 --> 01:03:28.400 align:middle line:84%
In some ways, I think death is
the most important experience

01:03:28.400 --> 01:03:31.370 align:middle line:84%
that you're preparing
for all your life.

01:03:31.370 --> 01:03:34.310 align:middle line:84%
>> Why is it so important
to talk about death?

01:03:34.310 --> 01:03:39.800 align:middle line:84%
It's the unspoken
phobia of the culture.

01:03:39.800 --> 01:03:44.450 align:middle line:10%
You can see it if you look at
the major issues like abortion,

01:03:44.450 --> 01:03:49.340 align:middle line:10%
death penalty,
euthanasia, terrorism.

01:03:49.340 --> 01:03:51.670 align:middle line:84%
It all concerns
this issue of death.

01:03:51.670 --> 01:03:56.340 align:middle line:90%


01:03:56.340 --> 01:03:58.380 align:middle line:84%
>> When I discovered
I was dying,

01:03:58.380 --> 01:04:03.760 align:middle line:84%
and I knew I was going to
die actively and creatively,

01:04:03.760 --> 01:04:07.990 align:middle line:84%
I called Ram Dass, because
I knew he would understand.

01:04:07.990 --> 01:04:10.730 align:middle line:90%


01:04:10.730 --> 01:04:14.445 align:middle line:84%
That's the galley of some
book I wrote years ago.

01:04:14.445 --> 01:04:19.240 align:middle line:84%
He's a wise friend and a
loving, protective friend

01:04:19.240 --> 01:04:23.030 align:middle line:84%
over many years and
many experiences.

01:04:23.030 --> 01:04:25.580 align:middle line:10%
>> Tim and I, in
1963 with Ralph,

01:04:25.580 --> 01:04:28.370 align:middle line:10%
were doing "The
Psychedelic Experience,"

01:04:28.370 --> 01:04:32.030 align:middle line:10%
which was a manual based on
"The Tibetan Book of the Dead."

01:04:32.030 --> 01:04:34.743 align:middle line:84%
And that led to a pretty
deep study of psychedelics.

01:04:34.743 --> 01:04:36.410 align:middle line:84%
And since we were
both dealing with what

01:04:36.410 --> 01:04:38.990 align:middle line:84%
we considered psychological
death and rebirth,

01:04:38.990 --> 01:04:41.540 align:middle line:84%
and we had been through those
death-rebirth experiences

01:04:41.540 --> 01:04:44.930 align:middle line:84%
many times together,
it's reasonable for him

01:04:44.930 --> 01:04:48.800 align:middle line:84%
to think of me as somebody
who would understand

01:04:48.800 --> 01:04:51.830 align:middle line:84%
what this death experience
was going to be like for him.

01:04:51.830 --> 01:04:54.764 align:middle line:90%
[GUTTURAL SINGING]

01:04:54.764 --> 01:04:56.231 align:middle line:90%


01:04:56.231 --> 01:05:00.010 align:middle line:84%
>> "The Psychedelic Experience"
was the first modern book

01:05:00.010 --> 01:05:03.820 align:middle line:84%
to provide a map for
mind-expanding drug sessions,

01:05:03.820 --> 01:05:05.590 align:middle line:84%
much as "The Tibetan
Book of the Dead"

01:05:05.590 --> 01:05:10.120 align:middle line:84%
provided advice for traveling
through after-death states,

01:05:10.120 --> 01:05:13.125 align:middle line:84%
known to Tibetan
Buddhists as bardos.

01:05:13.125 --> 01:05:15.990 align:middle line:90%


01:05:15.990 --> 01:05:20.000 align:middle line:84%
>> "Bardo" actually
means "in between."

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:20.920 align:middle line:90%
This is a bardo too.

01:05:20.920 --> 01:05:22.930 align:middle line:90%
We are in the bardo of life.

01:05:22.930 --> 01:05:25.593 align:middle line:10%
They were talking about
the bardo connected

01:05:25.593 --> 01:05:27.010 align:middle line:10%
to "The Tibetan
Book of the Dead,"

01:05:27.010 --> 01:05:30.700 align:middle line:10%
the bardo between
death and rebirth.

01:05:30.700 --> 01:05:36.400 align:middle line:10%
And they identified
LSD as a vehicle

01:05:36.400 --> 01:05:41.530 align:middle line:10%
to pre-experience what
that would be like.

01:05:41.530 --> 01:05:43.750 align:middle line:84%
>> Long before I
knew I was dying,

01:05:43.750 --> 01:05:47.270 align:middle line:84%
we were using this metaphor
of leaving your body,

01:05:47.270 --> 01:05:53.320 align:middle line:84%
leaving your mind, and
contacting a different level

01:05:53.320 --> 01:05:57.100 align:middle line:84%
of altered states,
expanded consciousness.

01:05:57.100 --> 01:05:59.710 align:middle line:84%
So my life has
prepared me for this.

01:05:59.710 --> 01:06:02.680 align:middle line:90%


01:06:02.680 --> 01:06:09.580 align:middle line:10%
>> I've seen so many people
die clinging to the past,

01:06:09.580 --> 01:06:14.030 align:middle line:10%
and also worried
about the future.

01:06:14.030 --> 01:06:17.020 align:middle line:90%
I think this is the moment.

01:06:17.020 --> 01:06:20.000 align:middle line:84%
That's what I got,
is this moment.

01:06:20.000 --> 01:06:24.610 align:middle line:84%
And one of these
moments, I'll be dead.

01:06:24.610 --> 01:06:28.000 align:middle line:90%
And that'll be the moment.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:32.440 align:middle line:84%
>> In 1977, Ram Dass founded
The Dying Project with Stephen

01:06:32.440 --> 01:06:34.525 align:middle line:84%
and Ondrea Levine
and Dale Borglum.

01:06:34.525 --> 01:06:37.030 align:middle line:90%


01:06:37.030 --> 01:06:41.530 align:middle line:84%
He's been a kind of midwife to
the dying since 1963, offering

01:06:41.530 --> 01:06:44.710 align:middle line:84%
wisdom, compassion, and his
knowledge of other planes

01:06:44.710 --> 01:06:46.000 align:middle line:90%
of consciousness.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:47.870 align:middle line:90%
>> Ram Dass was the pioneer.

01:06:47.870 --> 01:06:50.020 align:middle line:10%
He's the person who
really opened up

01:06:50.020 --> 01:06:54.370 align:middle line:10%
that field, for me personally.

01:06:54.370 --> 01:06:58.990 align:middle line:84%
>> The amount of cost in
keeping people alive--

01:06:58.990 --> 01:07:01.600 align:middle line:84%
forget quality of life
now, just physically alive.

01:07:01.600 --> 01:07:05.320 align:middle line:84%
The Intensive Care Unit strategy
was finally prohibitive.

01:07:05.320 --> 01:07:06.640 align:middle line:90%
It was getting prohibitive.

01:07:06.640 --> 01:07:10.060 align:middle line:84%
It was just eating
up all the resources.

01:07:10.060 --> 01:07:13.390 align:middle line:84%
Then comes the hospice
movement, which says, oh, well,

01:07:13.390 --> 01:07:16.420 align:middle line:84%
what we've missed is that the
psychological part of dying

01:07:16.420 --> 01:07:18.220 align:middle line:90%
is also important.

01:07:18.220 --> 01:07:21.620 align:middle line:84%
And hospice is much cheaper
than intensive care units.

01:07:21.620 --> 01:07:24.670 align:middle line:84%
Well, all it requires is
that we accept the fact

01:07:24.670 --> 01:07:26.120 align:middle line:90%
that death exists.

01:07:26.120 --> 01:07:29.590 align:middle line:84%
And that's a big shift,
to accept death existing,

01:07:29.590 --> 01:07:32.640 align:middle line:84%
versus, it's a
failure and an enemy.

01:07:32.640 --> 01:07:39.550 align:middle line:84%
>> What Ram Dass did was
really inspire people to bring

01:07:39.550 --> 01:07:44.230 align:middle line:84%
spirituality and existential
questions into their awareness

01:07:44.230 --> 01:07:49.740 align:middle line:84%
so that they could not only
die well, but also live well.

01:07:49.740 --> 01:07:53.560 align:middle line:84%
>> I do a lot of grief
work with people.

01:07:53.560 --> 01:07:55.830 align:middle line:10%
And what I often
am finding myself

01:07:55.830 --> 01:08:01.170 align:middle line:10%
saying to people who have lost
their child or their spouse

01:08:01.170 --> 01:08:04.290 align:middle line:10%
after many years or something--

01:08:04.290 --> 01:08:06.480 align:middle line:10%
you will grieve, and
grieve, and grieve,

01:08:06.480 --> 01:08:09.150 align:middle line:10%
and you'll come up for air,
and think it's all over,

01:08:09.150 --> 01:08:10.080 align:middle line:10%
and I'll be strong.

01:08:10.080 --> 01:08:11.430 align:middle line:84%
And then you'll go
back under, and you'll

01:08:11.430 --> 01:08:12.450 align:middle line:90%
go through depressions.

01:08:12.450 --> 01:08:14.670 align:middle line:90%
And let it all run its course.

01:08:14.670 --> 01:08:15.630 align:middle line:90%
Don't push it.

01:08:15.630 --> 01:08:17.340 align:middle line:84%
Your mind will
recite all the ways

01:08:17.340 --> 01:08:19.680 align:middle line:84%
you've lost the person,
that you'll never

01:08:19.680 --> 01:08:23.790 align:middle line:84%
have the smell of their
body, all these things.

01:08:23.790 --> 01:08:24.720 align:middle line:90%
Milk it all.

01:08:24.720 --> 01:08:26.750 align:middle line:90%
Don't push it away.

01:08:26.750 --> 01:08:30.270 align:middle line:84%
But there will come a time
when your mind will quiet down

01:08:30.270 --> 01:08:31.850 align:middle line:90%
a little bit.

01:08:31.850 --> 01:08:34.830 align:middle line:84%
And in the quietness
of that moment,

01:08:34.830 --> 01:08:38.080 align:middle line:84%
the love that you ever
tasted with that person

01:08:38.080 --> 01:08:40.170 align:middle line:90%
will be living and present.

01:08:40.170 --> 01:08:42.479 align:middle line:84%
And then you'll realize
that what the essence was

01:08:42.479 --> 01:08:45.000 align:middle line:84%
that made you connect
with this person

01:08:45.000 --> 01:08:47.140 align:middle line:90%
has nothing to do with death.

01:08:47.140 --> 01:08:50.160 align:middle line:84%
That love transcends
death, basically.

01:08:50.160 --> 01:08:52.920 align:middle line:84%
But you're going to have to
find it out for yourself.

01:08:52.920 --> 01:08:55.380 align:middle line:90%
But it's true.

01:08:55.380 --> 01:08:57.149 align:middle line:10%
>> I had this tragic loss.

01:08:57.149 --> 01:09:03.479 align:middle line:10%
I had the great love of
my life drop dead on me.

01:09:03.479 --> 01:09:06.210 align:middle line:84%
I was getting this
huge overflowing

01:09:06.210 --> 01:09:07.689 align:middle line:90%
of love from other people.

01:09:07.689 --> 01:09:10.880 align:middle line:90%
And it was absolutely useless.

01:09:10.880 --> 01:09:12.787 align:middle line:84%
I felt like a black
hole for love.

01:09:12.787 --> 01:09:14.870 align:middle line:84%
It didn't make any difference
what everybody said.

01:09:14.870 --> 01:09:17.060 align:middle line:84%
They didn't understand
what it felt like.

01:09:17.060 --> 01:09:21.380 align:middle line:84%
And then I felt like they
were wasting their love on me,

01:09:21.380 --> 01:09:24.790 align:middle line:90%
which is a terrible feeling.

01:09:24.790 --> 01:09:29.380 align:middle line:84%
And I mentioned
this to Ram Dass.

01:09:29.380 --> 01:09:33.550 align:middle line:90%


01:09:33.550 --> 01:09:36.580 align:middle line:84%
I said, I feel like
a bottomless well.

01:09:36.580 --> 01:09:37.930 align:middle line:90%
You know what I mean?

01:09:37.930 --> 01:09:40.930 align:middle line:84%
Love goes in, and you never
hear anything hit bottom.

01:09:40.930 --> 01:09:43.660 align:middle line:84%
And he said, well,
consider the possibility

01:09:43.660 --> 01:09:47.080 align:middle line:84%
that it's not bottomless,
that it's very deep--

01:09:47.080 --> 01:10:01.990 align:middle line:90%


01:10:01.990 --> 01:10:05.080 align:middle line:84%
sorry-- and that, one day,
it will fill it with love.

01:10:05.080 --> 01:10:07.990 align:middle line:90%


01:10:07.990 --> 01:10:08.920 align:middle line:90%
And all that still--

01:10:08.920 --> 01:10:11.884 align:middle line:84%
[CLEARS THROAT] --it
still kind of gets me.

01:10:11.884 --> 01:10:15.350 align:middle line:90%


01:10:15.350 --> 01:10:19.150 align:middle line:84%
>> Death and someone dying is
an initiation that we as human

01:10:19.150 --> 01:10:21.010 align:middle line:90%
beings go through.

01:10:21.010 --> 01:10:22.390 align:middle line:90%
And it enriches us.

01:10:22.390 --> 01:10:24.370 align:middle line:90%
It deepens us.

01:10:24.370 --> 01:10:26.530 align:middle line:90%
It opens our hearts.

01:10:26.530 --> 01:10:28.360 align:middle line:90%
It's a terrible thing.

01:10:28.360 --> 01:10:33.610 align:middle line:84%
But I think it makes us
bigger, and deeper, and more

01:10:33.610 --> 01:10:36.160 align:middle line:90%
compassionate as people.

01:10:36.160 --> 01:10:40.330 align:middle line:90%


01:10:40.330 --> 01:10:43.240 align:middle line:10%
>> I found out I had
cancer about a year ago.

01:10:43.240 --> 01:10:46.510 align:middle line:10%
But the real pressure of it,
the symptomatic pressure of it,

01:10:46.510 --> 01:10:50.500 align:middle line:10%
is just in the last
two or three months.

01:10:50.500 --> 01:10:53.430 align:middle line:90%
I've had moments of deep pain.

01:10:53.430 --> 01:10:56.730 align:middle line:84%
I've had moments when the
pain pills would almost

01:10:56.730 --> 01:10:58.270 align:middle line:90%
knock me out.

01:10:58.270 --> 01:11:01.750 align:middle line:84%
And I was a source of
worry to my friends,

01:11:01.750 --> 01:11:04.180 align:middle line:90%
because I was suffering so much.

01:11:04.180 --> 01:11:09.240 align:middle line:84%
And it's been a shock to me
to discover that pain exists,

01:11:09.240 --> 01:11:12.495 align:middle line:84%
and it can really dominate
your consciousness.

01:11:12.495 --> 01:11:13.870 align:middle line:84%
So I've had to
work that through.

01:11:13.870 --> 01:11:18.150 align:middle line:90%


01:11:18.150 --> 01:11:20.430 align:middle line:84%
>> See, the issue is
pain and consciousness,

01:11:20.430 --> 01:11:22.590 align:middle line:84%
the relation of pain
to consciousness.

01:11:22.590 --> 01:11:26.190 align:middle line:84%
Because when you're looking at
it from just the physical body,

01:11:26.190 --> 01:11:28.620 align:middle line:84%
the goal is to get rid of as
much pain as possible, even

01:11:28.620 --> 01:11:31.410 align:middle line:84%
if you have to put
the person to sleep,

01:11:31.410 --> 01:11:33.450 align:middle line:90%
keep them asleep until they die.

01:11:33.450 --> 01:11:37.800 align:middle line:84%
That's the most
humane thing to do.

01:11:37.800 --> 01:11:42.970 align:middle line:90%
Here we are six years later.

01:11:42.970 --> 01:11:47.800 align:middle line:84%
And I've had a stroke,
five years ago.

01:11:47.800 --> 01:11:49.510 align:middle line:90%
I don't remember time.

01:11:49.510 --> 01:11:52.555 align:middle line:90%
But this is now '03.

01:11:52.555 --> 01:11:57.550 align:middle line:90%


01:11:57.550 --> 01:12:01.690 align:middle line:84%
>> In February 1997, Ram
Dass suffered a severe stroke

01:12:01.690 --> 01:12:04.660 align:middle line:84%
and a massive
cerebral hemorrhage.

01:12:04.660 --> 01:12:07.115 align:middle line:84%
Doctors gave him only a
10% chance of survival.

01:12:07.115 --> 01:12:10.440 align:middle line:90%


01:12:10.440 --> 01:12:12.180 align:middle line:84%
Hundreds of hours
of rehabilitation

01:12:12.180 --> 01:12:15.780 align:middle line:84%
later, he was still partially
paralyzed, though able

01:12:15.780 --> 01:12:19.310 align:middle line:90%
to get around in a wheelchair.

01:12:19.310 --> 01:12:22.400 align:middle line:84%
After years of service,
he had to learn

01:12:22.400 --> 01:12:24.620 align:middle line:90%
to accept the help of others.

01:12:24.620 --> 01:12:38.390 align:middle line:84%
>> I am more now identified with
my soul and more compassionate

01:12:38.390 --> 01:12:41.540 align:middle line:90%
to my body.

01:12:41.540 --> 01:12:44.720 align:middle line:84%
See, I don't know how I'll
be if I'm in your situation.

01:12:44.720 --> 01:12:46.460 align:middle line:84%
At this moment, I
don't feel anxious

01:12:46.460 --> 01:12:49.040 align:middle line:84%
at all about my
life or anything.

01:12:49.040 --> 01:12:50.520 align:middle line:90%
>> Anything, yeah, yeah.

01:12:50.520 --> 01:12:59.460 align:middle line:84%
>> The stroke was so painful
that I pushed it away by going

01:12:59.460 --> 01:13:08.260 align:middle line:84%
to the witness in the soul, just
witnessing the stroke rather

01:13:08.260 --> 01:13:11.830 align:middle line:90%
than experiencing the stroke--

01:13:11.830 --> 01:13:19.650 align:middle line:84%
what a psychologist
would label dissociation.

01:13:19.650 --> 01:13:21.670 align:middle line:90%
Sure.

01:13:21.670 --> 01:13:22.589 align:middle line:90%
Yeah!

01:13:22.589 --> 01:13:26.720 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

01:13:26.720 --> 01:13:32.180 align:middle line:10%
My pains I treat lovingly.

01:13:32.180 --> 01:13:36.660 align:middle line:90%
Pain is a worthy adversary.

01:13:36.660 --> 01:13:40.170 align:middle line:84%
We're going to have
to fight it out.

01:13:40.170 --> 01:13:43.350 align:middle line:90%
>> He has been through a lot.

01:13:43.350 --> 01:13:45.030 align:middle line:90%
It's interesting to be with him.

01:13:45.030 --> 01:13:48.030 align:middle line:84%
Because there's an absence
of self-pity there.

01:13:48.030 --> 01:13:51.090 align:middle line:84%
And the fact that he's been
in that chair for 15 years,

01:13:51.090 --> 01:13:53.335 align:middle line:90%
I mean, that is no joke.

01:13:53.335 --> 01:13:54.390 align:middle line:90%
He's over 80 now.

01:13:54.390 --> 01:13:56.940 align:middle line:84%
That's really remarkable
that he's lived so long.

01:13:56.940 --> 01:14:00.240 align:middle line:84%
It's a testimony to his
delightful determination

01:14:00.240 --> 01:14:04.440 align:middle line:84%
that I think is a kind
of model for all of us.

01:14:04.440 --> 01:14:06.540 align:middle line:84%
There's something
about his essence

01:14:06.540 --> 01:14:08.580 align:middle line:90%
which has not changed at all.

01:14:08.580 --> 01:14:09.720 align:middle line:90%
I really feel it's love.

01:14:09.720 --> 01:14:15.030 align:middle line:90%


01:14:15.030 --> 01:14:18.960 align:middle line:84%
>> Ram Dass now lives in
Hawaii, cared for by a community

01:14:18.960 --> 01:14:21.199 align:middle line:90%
of loving friends and students.

01:14:21.199 --> 01:14:21.999 align:middle line:90%
>> Ah!

01:14:21.999 --> 01:14:24.580 align:middle line:90%


01:14:24.580 --> 01:14:25.380 align:middle line:90%
>> Woo-hoo!

01:14:25.380 --> 01:14:26.840 align:middle line:90%
Woo!

01:14:26.840 --> 01:14:31.640 align:middle line:84%
>> He's more active than ever,
teaching, writing, counseling,

01:14:31.640 --> 01:14:32.900 align:middle line:90%
and appearing virtually.

01:14:32.900 --> 01:14:36.233 align:middle line:90%
>> My body is 80 years old.

01:14:36.233 --> 01:14:40.250 align:middle line:90%
I am a soul.

01:14:40.250 --> 01:14:42.110 align:middle line:84%
>> Although still
physically restricted,

01:14:42.110 --> 01:14:45.510 align:middle line:84%
he continues his work,
furthering the vision he

01:14:45.510 --> 01:14:49.120 align:middle line:84%
pioneered with Timothy Leary
more than 40 years ago.

01:14:49.120 --> 01:14:53.640 align:middle line:10%
Adding to his personal legacy
is a son, Peter Reichard.

01:14:53.640 --> 01:14:56.850 align:middle line:10%
Ram Dass was introduced
to him in 2009.

01:14:56.850 --> 01:14:59.310 align:middle line:90%
It was a shock to both of them.

01:14:59.310 --> 01:15:00.110 align:middle line:90%
>> Wow.

01:15:00.110 --> 01:15:01.740 align:middle line:90%
In a million years!

01:15:01.740 --> 01:15:03.300 align:middle line:90%
Of all the crazy things.

01:15:03.300 --> 01:15:07.440 align:middle line:84%
And what a great
guy, Peter, his son.

01:15:07.440 --> 01:15:09.540 align:middle line:84%
>> Peter had never
heard of Ram Dass,

01:15:09.540 --> 01:15:12.660 align:middle line:84%
let alone that he was
his biological father.

01:15:12.660 --> 01:15:15.360 align:middle line:84%
Long ago, Richard Alpert
had a brief affair

01:15:15.360 --> 01:15:16.800 align:middle line:84%
with Peter's mother
while teaching

01:15:16.800 --> 01:15:20.700 align:middle line:84%
at Stanford, before his Harvard
years with Timothy Leary.

01:15:20.700 --> 01:15:23.820 align:middle line:84%
Peter was the result. But his
mother had moved back east

01:15:23.820 --> 01:15:25.830 align:middle line:90%
and never told Richard.

01:15:25.830 --> 01:15:28.560 align:middle line:84%
Now, more than 50
years later, Ram Dass

01:15:28.560 --> 01:15:32.040 align:middle line:84%
finds himself connected to
a new and growing family

01:15:32.040 --> 01:15:35.490 align:middle line:84%
in the final years of
his current incarnation.

01:15:35.490 --> 01:15:36.910 align:middle line:90%
>> The amazing thing--

01:15:36.910 --> 01:15:38.730 align:middle line:84%
the great singular
accomplishment

01:15:38.730 --> 01:15:42.450 align:middle line:84%
of Ram Dass's life, I
think, is that, setting up

01:15:42.450 --> 01:15:46.280 align:middle line:84%
from not very
promising beginnings,

01:15:46.280 --> 01:15:53.500 align:middle line:84%
he has become a truly
wise person, deeply.

01:15:53.500 --> 01:15:57.130 align:middle line:84%
>> If you see that the moment
of death is the moment when you

01:15:57.130 --> 01:16:00.340 align:middle line:84%
engage in the deepest
mystery of the universe--

01:16:00.340 --> 01:16:02.650 align:middle line:84%
and that's what the whole
Eastern traditions are about,

01:16:02.650 --> 01:16:06.190 align:middle line:84%
preparing you for that moment,
so that you will be equanimous.

01:16:06.190 --> 01:16:09.220 align:middle line:90%
You will be curious.

01:16:09.220 --> 01:16:10.330 align:middle line:90%
You'll be present.

01:16:10.330 --> 01:16:13.150 align:middle line:84%
You'll be non-clinging to
the past and not grabbing.

01:16:13.150 --> 01:16:18.340 align:middle line:84%
Just be with each
moment, moment by moment.

01:16:18.340 --> 01:16:21.970 align:middle line:84%
Some people do some of their
most profound spiritual work

01:16:21.970 --> 01:16:23.930 align:middle line:84%
in the last few minutes
before they die.

01:16:23.930 --> 01:16:28.820 align:middle line:90%


01:16:28.820 --> 01:16:30.680 align:middle line:90%
>> Wanting to get a head start--

01:16:30.680 --> 01:16:32.570 align:middle line:84%
why leave it to
the last minute--

01:16:32.570 --> 01:16:36.290 align:middle line:84%
Timothy Leary at 75
approached his final days

01:16:36.290 --> 01:16:38.810 align:middle line:90%
with characteristic enthusiasm.

01:16:38.810 --> 01:16:43.760 align:middle line:84%
He promised to give death a
better name or die trying.

01:16:43.760 --> 01:16:45.200 align:middle line:90%
>> We're all going to die.

01:16:45.200 --> 01:16:49.490 align:middle line:84%
Why not learn how to do it with
class and style and friendship

01:16:49.490 --> 01:16:52.630 align:middle line:84%
as the climactic
expression of a life?

01:16:52.630 --> 01:16:56.540 align:middle line:84%
The last week, I have
not been using any pills.

01:16:56.540 --> 01:17:02.560 align:middle line:84%
And it's been a fascinating and
wonderful experience-- so far.

01:17:02.560 --> 01:17:04.700 align:middle line:84%
I've become very
friendly with my cancer.

01:17:04.700 --> 01:17:10.130 align:middle line:84%
And also, I say in public, my
cancer I see now as my teacher.

01:17:10.130 --> 01:17:11.840 align:middle line:90%
And I try to talk to her.

01:17:11.840 --> 01:17:14.380 align:middle line:90%
And I say, Miss Cancer--

01:17:14.380 --> 01:17:15.945 align:middle line:90%
I say, we're in it together.

01:17:15.945 --> 01:17:17.690 align:middle line:90%
>> [LAUGHS] Yeah.

01:17:17.690 --> 01:17:18.822 align:middle line:90%
If you go, it goes.

01:17:18.822 --> 01:17:20.745 align:middle line:84%
>> We're both stuck
in the same body, see?

01:17:20.745 --> 01:17:21.290 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes, exactly.

01:17:21.290 --> 01:17:22.290 align:middle line:90%
>> So let's make a deal.

01:17:22.290 --> 01:17:24.560 align:middle line:84%
[CHUCKLES] Let's keep the
body alive a little while,

01:17:24.560 --> 01:17:26.587 align:middle line:90%
and we can have more fun.

01:17:26.587 --> 01:17:30.790 align:middle line:90%
>> [LAUGHS]

01:17:30.790 --> 01:17:34.190 align:middle line:84%
>> When the heart waves
flatline, the brain goes on.

01:17:34.190 --> 01:17:36.890 align:middle line:84%
They call it the
sliver of opportunity.

01:17:36.890 --> 01:17:38.860 align:middle line:84%
Your life flashes
in front of you.

01:17:38.860 --> 01:17:40.190 align:middle line:90%
>> And you go into ecstasy.

01:17:40.190 --> 01:17:41.520 align:middle line:84%
>> The light at the
end of the tunnel?

01:17:41.520 --> 01:17:42.080 align:middle line:90%
>> Sure, sure.

01:17:42.080 --> 01:17:44.390 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, that's all comes
from near-death experiences.

01:17:44.390 --> 01:17:45.315 align:middle line:90%
The brain is happy.

01:17:45.315 --> 01:17:46.940 align:middle line:84%
Because then the
brain is in the states

01:17:46.940 --> 01:17:48.330 align:middle line:90%
that the Buddhists talk about.

01:17:48.330 --> 01:17:49.125 align:middle line:90%
It's pure consciousness.

01:17:49.125 --> 01:17:49.925 align:middle line:90%
>> Sure.

01:17:49.925 --> 01:17:51.890 align:middle line:84%
It's extricated itself
from all the senses.

01:17:51.890 --> 01:17:52.690 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

01:17:52.690 --> 01:17:55.610 align:middle line:84%
But see, that 15 minutes is
timeless, like an LSD session.

01:17:55.610 --> 01:17:56.410 align:middle line:90%
>> Mm-hmm.

01:17:56.410 --> 01:17:58.890 align:middle line:84%
>> You go through 95
lifetimes in death.

01:17:58.890 --> 01:18:00.313 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, every
minute is timeless.

01:18:00.313 --> 01:18:01.230 align:middle line:90%
>> There you go, yeah.

01:18:01.230 --> 01:18:02.860 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

01:18:02.860 --> 01:18:04.660 align:middle line:84%
>> Like everybody
else, I'm speculating.

01:18:04.660 --> 01:18:05.770 align:middle line:90%
And I may change.

01:18:05.770 --> 01:18:08.620 align:middle line:10%
I'm trying to learn.

01:18:08.620 --> 01:18:11.550 align:middle line:84%
>> This period that
Timothy Leary speaks about,

01:18:11.550 --> 01:18:17.130 align:middle line:84%
this 15 to 20-minute period,
what that would be called

01:18:17.130 --> 01:18:21.710 align:middle line:84%
in the Tibetan teaching is
still the process of dying.

01:18:21.710 --> 01:18:23.800 align:middle line:90%
So you're not dead yet.

01:18:23.800 --> 01:18:26.740 align:middle line:84%
But the gross body is
dead, but the subtle body

01:18:26.740 --> 01:18:28.370 align:middle line:90%
is still remaining in the body.

01:18:28.370 --> 01:18:31.560 align:middle line:90%
So that's what he's identifying.

01:18:31.560 --> 01:18:33.390 align:middle line:84%
>> At this period
in human history,

01:18:33.390 --> 01:18:38.060 align:middle line:84%
we're lucky enough to be here
when, for the first times,

01:18:38.060 --> 01:18:41.370 align:middle line:84%
science is developing ways to
keep you alive or to bring you

01:18:41.370 --> 01:18:42.180 align:middle line:90%
back.

01:18:42.180 --> 01:18:44.730 align:middle line:84%
The church has said, no,
you have no right to take--

01:18:44.730 --> 01:18:46.020 align:middle line:90%
your body belongs to God.

01:18:46.020 --> 01:18:49.732 align:middle line:90%
Well, show me the paperwork.

01:18:49.732 --> 01:18:52.690 align:middle line:90%
[THUNDER]

01:18:52.690 --> 01:18:56.520 align:middle line:84%
>> By 1993, Timothy and
Barbara had divorced,

01:18:56.520 --> 01:18:59.350 align:middle line:84%
although Tim remained
close to her son Zach.

01:18:59.350 --> 01:19:01.650 align:middle line:84%
>> He had a lot of personal
heartache in his life.

01:19:01.650 --> 01:19:03.630 align:middle line:84%
His wife Marianne
killed herself.

01:19:03.630 --> 01:19:06.020 align:middle line:10%
And every marriage
ended in divorce.

01:19:06.020 --> 01:19:08.025 align:middle line:10%
His daughter Susan
also committed suicide.

01:19:08.025 --> 01:19:09.750 align:middle line:10%
And Jack didn't speak to him.

01:19:09.750 --> 01:19:12.422 align:middle line:84%
So there was a lot
of heavy stuff going

01:19:12.422 --> 01:19:14.130 align:middle line:84%
on there, a lot of
heavy karmas and a lot

01:19:14.130 --> 01:19:16.530 align:middle line:84%
of interpersonal relationships
that he just really

01:19:16.530 --> 01:19:18.060 align:middle line:90%
couldn't work out.

01:19:18.060 --> 01:19:22.200 align:middle line:84%
And I think that
really broke his heart.

01:19:22.200 --> 01:19:26.100 align:middle line:84%
And there was no question that
him getting to raise me again

01:19:26.100 --> 01:19:30.490 align:middle line:84%
was a chance for him
to do it over again.

01:19:30.490 --> 01:19:34.050 align:middle line:84%
He had an uncanny knack
to reinvent himself.

01:19:34.050 --> 01:19:36.600 align:middle line:84%
Especially in the late
'80s and into the '90s,

01:19:36.600 --> 01:19:39.570 align:middle line:84%
he was much more of
a cyber culture icon

01:19:39.570 --> 01:19:42.240 align:middle line:90%
than he was a '60s hippie icon.

01:19:42.240 --> 01:19:44.070 align:middle line:84%
And that's why he kept
young people around,

01:19:44.070 --> 01:19:46.950 align:middle line:84%
because he was so fascinated
with youth culture,

01:19:46.950 --> 01:19:49.080 align:middle line:84%
and with computer
culture, and early

01:19:49.080 --> 01:19:52.890 align:middle line:84%
internet culture, and cyberpunk
culture, and music culture,

01:19:52.890 --> 01:19:54.450 align:middle line:90%
and art.

01:19:54.450 --> 01:19:57.740 align:middle line:84%
>> Every technique that science
has now for bringing you back

01:19:57.740 --> 01:19:58.930 align:middle line:90%
I've been signed up with.

01:19:58.930 --> 01:20:00.720 align:middle line:90%
[THUNDER]

01:20:00.720 --> 01:20:03.060 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to have my blood
cells available for cloning.

01:20:03.060 --> 01:20:04.860 align:middle line:90%
[EXPLOSION]

01:20:04.860 --> 01:20:07.800 align:middle line:10%
>> It's inconceivable to me
that Timothy could have taken

01:20:07.800 --> 01:20:10.020 align:middle line:10%
as much acid as he's taken
and been through as much

01:20:10.020 --> 01:20:14.130 align:middle line:10%
as he's been through and end
up a philosophical materialist

01:20:14.130 --> 01:20:16.680 align:middle line:10%
in which, when the body
is dead, you're dead.

01:20:16.680 --> 01:20:18.540 align:middle line:90%
Yet that's what he professed.

01:20:18.540 --> 01:20:21.120 align:middle line:84%
Why did it end up that
you're interested in things

01:20:21.120 --> 01:20:24.410 align:middle line:84%
here and now, and I'm interested
in lala land all the time?

01:20:24.410 --> 01:20:25.210 align:middle line:90%
Why is that?

01:20:25.210 --> 01:20:26.160 align:middle line:90%
>> You're not really.

01:20:26.160 --> 01:20:26.970 align:middle line:90%
>> I am.

01:20:26.970 --> 01:20:27.490 align:middle line:90%
I am.

01:20:27.490 --> 01:20:27.840 align:middle line:90%
>> What do you mean?

01:20:27.840 --> 01:20:28.640 align:middle line:90%
What's lala land?

01:20:28.640 --> 01:20:31.740 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I'm interested in the
awareness that happens after

01:20:31.740 --> 01:20:35.280 align:middle line:90%
the brain gets eaten.

01:20:35.280 --> 01:20:37.860 align:middle line:84%
When I think about
the moment of death,

01:20:37.860 --> 01:20:40.890 align:middle line:84%
I usually think of
a great acid trip.

01:20:40.890 --> 01:20:44.770 align:middle line:84%
I think of the dissolution
of conceptual structures.

01:20:44.770 --> 01:20:49.680 align:middle line:90%


01:20:49.680 --> 01:20:52.620 align:middle line:84%
I have, under my
personal supervision,

01:20:52.620 --> 01:20:56.130 align:middle line:84%
witnessed over 3,000
injections of LSD.

01:20:56.130 --> 01:20:58.530 align:middle line:90%
>> Over 3,000.

01:20:58.530 --> 01:21:02.020 align:middle line:10%
Well, can you briefly
describe the effect of it?

01:21:02.020 --> 01:21:05.880 align:middle line:10%
>> [LAUGHS] No, sir.

01:21:05.880 --> 01:21:08.520 align:middle line:84%
You might say I
was sitting there,

01:21:08.520 --> 01:21:10.500 align:middle line:84%
and suddenly, I
began to dissolve.

01:21:10.500 --> 01:21:13.583 align:middle line:84%
Every cell in my body
began to break down.

01:21:13.583 --> 01:21:15.000 align:middle line:84%
And it was though
I was afraid I'd

01:21:15.000 --> 01:21:17.550 align:middle line:90%
become a puddle on the floor.

01:21:17.550 --> 01:21:21.300 align:middle line:84%
Then I saw a huge
serpent coming up.

01:21:21.300 --> 01:21:22.950 align:middle line:90%
The serpent swallowed me.

01:21:22.950 --> 01:21:25.770 align:middle line:84%
I went into the
serpent's stomach.

01:21:25.770 --> 01:21:28.490 align:middle line:84%
Later, I was excreted,
and I exploded.

01:21:28.490 --> 01:21:29.290 align:middle line:10%
Then--

01:21:29.290 --> 01:21:32.070 align:middle line:10%
>> You see Teddy Kennedy there.

01:21:32.070 --> 01:21:33.180 align:middle line:90%
It's like, oh, my gosh.

01:21:33.180 --> 01:21:36.870 align:middle line:84%
These guys must have been
having their own little mental

01:21:36.870 --> 01:21:38.600 align:middle line:90%
breakdown listening to him.

01:21:38.600 --> 01:21:41.130 align:middle line:84%
>> And by this time,
even the most experienced

01:21:41.130 --> 01:21:43.950 align:middle line:84%
and hard-bitten psychiatrist
is likely to be crouching under

01:21:43.950 --> 01:21:46.470 align:middle line:84%
the table and saying, in
30 years of my practice,

01:21:46.470 --> 01:21:50.160 align:middle line:84%
I've never listened to anything
so frightening and so far out.

01:21:50.160 --> 01:21:53.310 align:middle line:84%
Now, actually, if you told
this story to a Hindu,

01:21:53.310 --> 01:21:56.192 align:middle line:84%
he'd say, oh, yes, the
third dream of Vishnu.

01:21:56.192 --> 01:21:58.650 align:middle line:84%
Oh, yes, that's just like the
11th chapter of "The Bhagavad

01:21:58.650 --> 01:21:59.670 align:middle line:90%
Gita."

01:21:59.670 --> 01:22:05.160 align:middle line:84%
But we also have neurological
and anatomical explanations

01:22:05.160 --> 01:22:08.790 align:middle line:84%
for the so-called
hallucinations of LSD.

01:22:08.790 --> 01:22:11.670 align:middle line:84%
Hallucinations are not
mysterious or supernatural.

01:22:11.670 --> 01:22:14.580 align:middle line:84%
Hallucinations are the nervous
system having experiences

01:22:14.580 --> 01:22:16.170 align:middle line:90%
for which we don't have words.

01:22:16.170 --> 01:22:20.100 align:middle line:84%
>> It's the dying process
of the psychological realm.

01:22:20.100 --> 01:22:24.030 align:middle line:84%
It's the kind of dissolving
of the perspective

01:22:24.030 --> 01:22:25.920 align:middle line:90%
from which you're standing.

01:22:25.920 --> 01:22:28.410 align:middle line:84%
That, to me, is one of the
things that's happening

01:22:28.410 --> 01:22:30.510 align:middle line:90%
while people are dying.

01:22:30.510 --> 01:22:32.820 align:middle line:84%
And then, I feel,
you're catapulted out

01:22:32.820 --> 01:22:35.260 align:middle line:90%
into non-conceptual space.

01:22:35.260 --> 01:22:36.917 align:middle line:84%
Is that the way
you're imagining it?

01:22:36.917 --> 01:22:37.875 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, yeah, exactly.

01:22:37.875 --> 01:22:38.675 align:middle line:90%
Brilliant.

01:22:38.675 --> 01:22:45.990 align:middle line:10%
>> So my sense of the continuity
of awareness beyond the brain

01:22:45.990 --> 01:22:49.650 align:middle line:10%
is just my wanting to
keep something going?

01:22:49.650 --> 01:22:50.670 align:middle line:90%
>> I don't have that.

01:22:50.670 --> 01:22:52.905 align:middle line:90%
>> I know you don't have it.

01:22:52.905 --> 01:22:54.520 align:middle line:90%
>> I'm curious.

01:22:54.520 --> 01:22:55.320 align:middle line:90%
>> You're curious.

01:22:55.320 --> 01:22:55.860 align:middle line:90%
I'm curious too.

01:22:55.860 --> 01:22:56.693 align:middle line:90%
>> I'm very curious.

01:22:56.693 --> 01:22:59.973 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

01:22:59.973 --> 01:23:09.960 align:middle line:90%


01:23:09.960 --> 01:23:11.420 align:middle line:90%
>> Do you use the word "soul?"

01:23:11.420 --> 01:23:11.690 align:middle line:90%
>> Soul?

01:23:11.690 --> 01:23:12.200 align:middle line:90%
All the time.

01:23:12.200 --> 01:23:13.230 align:middle line:90%
